-- FIRST TRIMESTER: SYMPTOMS & EXPERIENCE
-- ============================================================

('pregnancy', 6, 'Morning Sickness: Why It Happens and What Actually Helps',
 'The science behind nausea in pregnancy — and strategies that make a real difference',
 E'## Why nausea happens in early pregnancy\n\nMorning sickness affects around 70\u201380% of pregnant people, and despite the name, it can strike at any time of day. The primary driver is the rapid rise of human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) \u2014 the hormone produced by the developing placenta. Levels of hCG peak between weeks 8 and 10, which is why nausea is often worst during this period and tends to ease in the second trimester.\n\nOestrogen also rises sharply in early pregnancy and is thought to heighten sensitivity to smells, which can trigger or worsen nausea. Low blood sugar from going too long without food adds another layer.\n\n## What actually helps\n\n**Eat before you get up.** Keep plain crackers, dry toast, or rice cakes by your bed. Eating something small before you even sit up can prevent the blood sugar dip that triggers early morning nausea.\n\n**Small, frequent meals.** An empty stomach makes nausea worse. Aim for something small every 2\u20133 hours rather than three large meals.\n\n**Cold and bland foods.** Hot foods release stronger aromas. Cold or room-temperature options \u2014 fruit, yoghurt, plain rice, cold noodles \u2014 are often better tolerated.\n\n**Ginger.** There is genuine evidence that ginger helps reduce nausea in pregnancy. Ginger tea, ginger biscuits, ginger chews, or crystallised ginger can all be useful. Around 1\u20131.5g of ginger per day is what studies have used.\n\n**Vitamin B6 (pyridoxine).** This is a first-line treatment recommended by many obstetric bodies. Around 10\u201325mg taken two to three times daily has been shown to reduce nausea. Always check with your provider before starting.\n\n**Stay hydrated between meals.** Drinking large amounts with meals can worsen nausea. Try sipping fluids steadily between eating rather than with food.\n\n**Identify your triggers.** Certain smells, textures, or foods will be unique triggers for you. Keeping a brief log for a few days can help you identify patterns and avoid them.\n\n## When to seek help\n\nIf you cannot keep food or fluids down for more than 24 hours, are losing weight, feel dizzy or faint, or notice dark-coloured urine (a sign of dehydration), contact your healthcare provider. A small percentage of pregnant people develop hyperemesis gravidarum \u2014 severe, persistent vomiting that requires medical treatment including IV fluids and prescribed anti-nausea medication. This is a real medical condition, not a sign of weakness, and effective treatment is available.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only and does not replace advice from your healthcare provider. If you have concerns about nausea or vomiting in pregnancy, speak with your midwife or doctor.*',
 'health', 5, ARRAY['morning-sickness','nausea','first-trimester','hcg','ginger','vitamin-b6'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 6, 'Food Aversions and Cravings in the First Trimester',
 'Why your relationship with food changes so dramatically \u2014 and how to navigate it',
 E'## The hormonal explanation\n\nFood cravings and aversions during pregnancy are not imaginary, and they are not simply about indulgence. They are driven by the same hormonal surge \u2014 particularly rising hCG and oestrogen \u2014 that causes nausea. Oestrogen is known to heighten the sense of smell significantly, which is why a food that smelled perfectly fine six weeks ago might now make you want to leave the room.\n\nCravings are less well understood scientifically, but theories include micronutrient deficiency signals (craving red meat when iron is low, for example) and changes in taste perception driven by hormonal shifts.\n\n## Common aversions\n\nMeat, fish, eggs, coffee, and strongly spiced foods top the list of common first-trimester aversions. Cooking smells are often more problematic than the food itself. If this is the case for you, ask a partner or family member to cook when possible, use a kitchen fan, or lean on cold meals that require minimal cooking.\n\n## Common cravings\n\nCarbohydrate-rich, bland foods are among the most commonly craved \u2014 toast, crackers, pasta, rice. Some people crave intensely salty or sour things. Fruit is a very common craving and generally a nutritionally sound one.\n\nIf you are craving non-food items \u2014 ice, dirt, chalk, clay \u2014 this is called pica, and you should mention it to your healthcare provider. It can be associated with iron or zinc deficiency.\n\n## Navigating aversions nutritionally\n\nThe goal is to meet your nutritional needs from whatever you can actually eat, not from what you ''should'' eat on paper. If meat is aversive, lentils, beans, tofu, and eggs (if tolerated) are strong protein and iron alternatives. If vegetables are difficult, fruit often remains tolerable and provides vitamins, fibre, and hydration.\n\nFirst trimester is not the time to stress about a perfect diet. Focus on staying hydrated and eating enough calories from whatever foods you can manage. Nutritional demands increase more significantly in the second and third trimesters when nausea typically eases.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider or a registered dietitian if food aversions are significantly affecting your nutrition.*',
 'nutrition', 4, ARRAY['cravings','aversions','first-trimester','nausea','nutrition','pica'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 5, 'Extreme Fatigue in Early Pregnancy: Why It Happens and How to Cope',
 'The tiredness of the first trimester is in a category of its own \u2014 here is why',
 E'## Why first-trimester fatigue is so intense\n\nThe fatigue most people experience in early pregnancy is not ordinary tiredness. Many describe it as the most exhausted they have ever felt \u2014 a bone-deep heaviness that makes ordinary tasks feel monumental. This is not exaggeration, and it is not a sign that something is wrong.\n\nYour body is doing extraordinary work. In the first trimester, you are building an entirely new organ \u2014 the placenta \u2014 while your blood volume begins to expand (it will increase by around 50% by the end of pregnancy), your heart works harder, your progesterone levels soar, and your metabolism increases. Progesterone in particular has a sedative effect, which is why sleep feels irresistible.\n\nLower blood pressure, changes in blood sugar regulation, and the demands of early fetal development all compound this.\n\n## When fatigue peaks\n\nFatigue tends to be worst between weeks 6 and 10, and for most people begins to ease noticeably in the second trimester as the placenta takes over hormone production and the body adapts to its new demands.\n\n## Practical strategies\n\n**Rest without guilt.** First trimester fatigue is a biological signal. If your body is demanding rest, resting is the right response. This is not laziness.\n\n**Prioritise sleep hygiene.** Going to bed earlier than usual, keeping screens out of the bedroom, and maintaining a consistent sleep schedule can improve the quality of sleep even when quantity feels never enough.\n\n**Eat regularly.** Blood sugar dips worsen fatigue significantly. Keeping easy snacks nearby \u2014 nuts, fruit, crackers with nut butter \u2014 and eating every few hours helps maintain steadier energy.\n\n**Gentle movement.** It may feel counterintuitive, but short gentle walks can improve energy levels over time by supporting circulation and mood. Do not push through exhaustion, but do not abandon movement entirely.\n\n**Communicate your needs.** At home, ask for help with meals, chores, and other demands. At work, use breaks and lunch time for rest if possible. You do not need to explain your pregnancy to justify needing rest.\n\n**Prioritise ruthlessly.** Identify what genuinely needs to happen each day and let everything else wait. This is temporary.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Persistent or extreme fatigue that does not improve should be discussed with your healthcare provider to rule out anaemia or thyroid issues.*',
 'wellness', 4, ARRAY['fatigue','first-trimester','progesterone','energy','rest','sleep'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 6, 'Spotting in Early Pregnancy: When to Worry and When Not To',
 'Light bleeding in early pregnancy is common \u2014 but knowing what is normal and what is not matters',
 E'## How common is early pregnancy spotting?\n\nAround 20\u201325% of pregnant people experience some light bleeding or spotting in the first trimester. Most of the time, it does not indicate a problem. However, any bleeding in pregnancy should be assessed by a healthcare provider \u2014 not because it is necessarily serious, but because the cause matters.\n\n## Common benign causes\n\n**Implantation bleeding.** Around 6\u201312 days after fertilisation, the embryo implants into the uterine lining. Some people notice light spotting \u2014 often pink or brown \u2014 at this stage. It typically lasts only a day or two and is lighter than a normal period.\n\n**Cervical sensitivity.** During pregnancy, the cervix becomes richly supplied with blood vessels and is more easily irritated. Light spotting after sex or a vaginal examination is very common and is not a sign of harm to the pregnancy.\n\n**Sub-chorionic haematoma.** A small collection of blood between the placenta and the uterine wall. Often detected on ultrasound, usually resolves on its own.\n\n## When to seek care promptly\n\nContact your healthcare provider or go to an emergency department if you experience:\n\n- Heavy bleeding (soaking a pad)\n- Bright red blood that is increasing in volume\n- Bleeding accompanied by significant cramping or pain, especially one-sided pain\n- Dizziness, shoulder tip pain, or feeling faint alongside bleeding\n- Passing tissue or clots\n\nOne-sided pain with bleeding can indicate an ectopic pregnancy \u2014 a pregnancy in the fallopian tube \u2014 which is a medical emergency requiring immediate assessment.\n\n## Miscarriage and bleeding\n\nNot all spotting leads to miscarriage, but miscarriage can cause bleeding. Passing tissue or clots, or heavy bleeding with cramping, warrants urgent assessment. A healthcare provider can assess via ultrasound and blood tests.\n\nWaiting for results is extremely hard. Reach out to your support network and speak with your provider about what they find and what it means for your pregnancy.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Any bleeding in pregnancy should be assessed by a healthcare provider. If you are concerned, do not wait \u2014 contact your provider or seek emergency care.*',
 'health', 4, ARRAY['spotting','bleeding','first-trimester','implantation','ectopic','miscarriage'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 8, 'Miscarriage Risk in the First Trimester: The Real Statistics',
 'Understanding the actual numbers \u2014 and what they mean for you',
 E'## What the statistics actually show\n\nMiscarriage is far more common than most people realise before they experience it. Around 10\u201320% of known pregnancies end in miscarriage, with the vast majority occurring in the first trimester. When pregnancies that end before a missed period are included (chemical pregnancies), the total is higher still.\n\nThe risk is not evenly distributed across the first trimester. Early in pregnancy \u2014 particularly before a heartbeat has been detected \u2014 risk is at its highest.\n\n- Before 6 weeks: risk can be 30\u201350%, though many of these end before a missed period\n- After a heartbeat is detected at 6\u20138 weeks: risk drops to around 3\u20135% in people without other risk factors\n- After 10 weeks: risk falls to approximately 1\u20132% for a continuing pregnancy\n\n## Why miscarriage happens\n\nThe overwhelming majority of first-trimester miscarriages are caused by chromosomal abnormalities in the embryo \u2014 a random error during cell division that makes development non-viable. This is not caused by anything you did or did not do. Exercise, sex, stress, a fall, an argument, food choices \u2014 none of these are causes of chromosomal miscarriage.\n\nOther causes include uterine structure issues, hormonal imbalances (such as poorly controlled thyroid disease), and antiphospholipid syndrome, which are far less common.\n\n## What increases risk\n\nAge is the most significant risk factor. The rate of chromosomal abnormalities in eggs increases with age, which is why miscarriage risk rises with maternal age \u2014 from around 10% in people in their 20s to 20\u201335% in those in their late 30s and early 40s.\n\nSmoking, heavy alcohol use, and poorly controlled chronic conditions such as diabetes also increase risk. Many risk factors, however, are not within anyone''s control.\n\n## Navigating the waiting\n\nMany people spend the first trimester in a state of anxious waiting \u2014 especially if they have experienced loss before. If you are finding this difficult, it is entirely reasonable to seek emotional support, speak with your provider about what monitoring is available to you, and give yourself permission to feel however you feel.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider about your individual risk and any concerns you have about your pregnancy.*',
 'mental-health', 5, ARRAY['miscarriage','first-trimester','risk','statistics','pregnancy-loss','chromosomal'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 4, 'Pregnancy Tests: When to Take One and What the Results Mean',
 'How home pregnancy tests work, when they are most accurate, and how to read the result',
 E'## How pregnancy tests work\n\nHome pregnancy tests detect human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), a hormone produced by the cells that will form the placenta, beginning shortly after the fertilised egg implants in the uterine wall. Most tests can detect hCG in urine from around the time of a missed period.\n\n## When to test\n\nThe most reliable time to take a pregnancy test is the first day of your missed period. Testing earlier increases the chance of a false negative \u2014 hCG levels may not yet be high enough for detection.\n\nSome ''early response'' tests claim to detect pregnancy 4\u20136 days before a missed period. These can work, but sensitivity varies between brands and individuals, and a negative result before a missed period should be retested if your period does not arrive.\n\n## Reading the result\n\n**Two lines (or a plus, or ''pregnant''):** A positive result. Even a very faint second line is a positive \u2014 any hCG presence sufficient to react with the test indicates pregnancy. Faint lines are more common when testing early.\n\n**One line (or a minus, or ''not pregnant''):** A negative result. If your period does not arrive within a week, retest. A negative result before a missed period may simply mean hCG was not yet high enough.\n\n**Invalid result:** If the control line does not appear, the test has not worked correctly. Retest with a new one.\n\n## After a positive test\n\nIf your test is positive, contact your GP or midwife to begin antenatal care. In many countries you will not have your first appointment until around 8\u201310 weeks, but you can register earlier. Start taking a prenatal vitamin with folic acid immediately if you are not already.\n\nConfirm the result with a second test if you want reassurance \u2014 this is completely normal and understandable.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. A positive home pregnancy test should be followed up with your healthcare provider to begin appropriate antenatal care.*',
 'health', 3, ARRAY['pregnancy-test','hcg','positive-result','first-trimester','planning'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 5, 'hCG Levels in Early Pregnancy: What They Mean',
 'Understanding the hormone that confirms your pregnancy \u2014 and what tracking its levels shows',
 E'## What is hCG?\n\nHuman chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) is the hormone produced by the developing placenta after implantation. It is what pregnancy tests detect, and it is responsible for signalling the ovaries to continue producing progesterone (which maintains the uterine lining) until the placenta can take over this role.\n\n## When hCG levels rise and fall\n\nhCG begins to appear in blood and urine around 10\u201314 days after fertilisation. In a healthy early pregnancy, levels typically double every 48\u201372 hours. They peak between weeks 8 and 10, then gradually decline to a lower plateau for the remainder of pregnancy.\n\nThis rise and subsequent fall is closely linked to the pattern of morning sickness \u2014 nausea tends to be worst when hCG peaks, and eases as levels fall in the second trimester.\n\n## What blood hCG tests show\n\nA single hCG reading is less informative than the trend over time. Reference ranges vary widely between individuals and labs \u2014 a ''normal'' hCG at 5 weeks can be anywhere from 18 to 7,340 mIU/mL. What matters more is whether the number is rising appropriately.\n\n**Doubling within 48\u201372 hours** suggests a normally progressing early pregnancy.\n\n**Levels that rise slowly, plateau, or fall** may indicate a pregnancy that is not progressing \u2014 though this needs to be confirmed with repeat testing and ultrasound.\n\n**Very high levels** can occasionally indicate a multiple pregnancy (twins or more) or, rarely, a molar pregnancy \u2014 a condition where abnormal tissue grows in the uterus.\n\n## When your provider will monitor hCG\n\nRoutine hCG monitoring is not standard practice in uncomplicated pregnancies \u2014 it is typically used when there is uncertainty about the location or viability of a pregnancy, or following fertility treatment. If your provider has recommended serial hCG tests, they will interpret the results in the context of your full clinical picture.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. hCG results should always be interpreted by a healthcare provider in the context of your specific situation.*',
 'health', 4, ARRAY['hcg','hormones','first-trimester','blood-test','pregnancy-viability'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 12, 'The 12-Week Scan: What to Expect and What It Shows',
 'Your first detailed look at your baby \u2014 and an important health check for you both',
 E'## What is the 12-week scan?\n\nThe 12-week scan, also called the dating scan or first trimester ultrasound, is typically offered between weeks 11 and 13+6. It is usually your first detailed ultrasound and serves several purposes at once.\n\n## What the sonographer is looking for\n\n**Dating the pregnancy.** The scan measures the baby from crown to rump (CRL), which gives a more accurate estimated due date than last menstrual period calculations \u2014 especially if your cycles are irregular.\n\n**Checking for multiples.** This is when twins, triplets, or higher-order multiples are confirmed. In twin pregnancies, the scan also establishes whether twins share a placenta (identical) or have separate placentas (fraternal or some identicals), which has implications for monitoring.\n\n**Basic anatomy check.** The sonographer will check that the heart is beating, that the limbs are present and visible, and that the brain, spine, and abdomen appear to be developing normally. This is not as detailed as the 20-week anatomy scan.\n\n**Nuchal translucency (NT) measurement.** The fluid-filled space at the back of the baby''s neck is measured. A thicker NT can be associated with chromosomal conditions such as Down syndrome and some heart defects. This result is combined with blood test results in the combined first trimester screen.\n\n## What to expect during the appointment\n\nMost 12-week scans are done abdominally, though a transvaginal scan may be used if the image is unclear. You may be asked to attend with a full bladder for an abdominal scan, as this improves visibility.\n\nThe appointment typically takes 20\u201345 minutes. You will likely see the baby moving and can usually get a printed image. If you wish to know the sex, you may be able to ask at this point, though confirmation is typically more reliable at the 20-week scan.\n\n## If something unexpected is found\n\nOccasionally the scan will identify something that needs follow-up \u2014 a slightly elevated NT, an uncertain finding, or a marker that prompts further testing. Try to hold space for uncertainty. Your provider will guide you through what any finding means and what the next steps are.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider or sonographer about your individual scan findings.*',
 'health', 5, ARRAY['12-week-scan','dating-scan','nuchal-translucency','first-trimester','ultrasound'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 11, 'First Trimester Screening: NIPT, NT Scan, and Combined Screening Explained',
 'Understanding the options for chromosomal screening in early pregnancy \u2014 what they detect, how they work, and what to do with results',
 E'## What is first trimester screening?\n\nFirst trimester screening refers to a group of tests offered between approximately weeks 10 and 14 that assess the likelihood of certain chromosomal conditions in the baby \u2014 most commonly Down syndrome (trisomy 21), Edwards syndrome (trisomy 18), and Patau syndrome (trisomy 13).\n\nThese are screening tests, not diagnostic tests. They estimate risk \u2014 they do not give a definitive answer. A positive or high-risk result means further diagnostic testing (CVS or amniocentesis) may be recommended.\n\n## Combined first trimester screening\n\nThe most widely offered screening in many countries combines:\n\n- **Nuchal translucency (NT) measurement** from the 11\u201313 week ultrasound\n- **Blood tests** measuring two hormones: PAPP-A (pregnancy-associated plasma protein A) and free beta-hCG\n- **Your age** (which affects baseline chromosomal risk)\n\nTogether, these produce a risk ratio (e.g., 1 in 5,000 or 1 in 80) for common chromosomal conditions. Detection rates are around 85\u201390% for Down syndrome with a 5% false-positive rate.\n\n## Non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT)\n\nNIPT analyses fragments of fetal DNA circulating in the mother''s blood. It is more accurate than combined screening \u2014 detection rates for Down syndrome exceed 99% \u2014 and can be done from week 10. It does not carry any risk to the pregnancy.\n\nNIPT is not a diagnostic test: a high-risk result still needs confirmation via invasive testing. A low-risk result is highly reassuring but not a guarantee.\n\nNIPT is available privately in most countries and increasingly available publicly, with eligibility criteria varying by location and healthcare system.\n\n## Diagnostic testing: CVS and amniocentesis\n\nChorionic villus sampling (CVS) is done around weeks 11\u201313 and amniocentesis around weeks 15\u201318. Both take a sample for chromosomal analysis and give definitive results. Both carry a small risk of miscarriage (around 0.5\u20131%) and are typically offered when screening suggests increased risk or when parents choose certainty over screening.\n\n## Making the decision\n\nScreening is always optional. Some parents want as much information as possible; others prefer not to know unless there is something they could act on. Both positions are valid. Genetic counsellors can help you think through the options before and after testing.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider or a genetic counsellor about what screening is right for you.*',
 'health', 6, ARRAY['nipt','nt-scan','combined-screening','chromosomal','down-syndrome','first-trimester','genetic-testing'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 12, 'Announcing Your Pregnancy: When and How to Tell People',
 'There is no single right time \u2014 here is how to think through what works for you',
 E'## The 12-week convention\n\nMany people wait until after the 12-week scan to announce their pregnancy publicly. The reasoning is that miscarriage risk drops significantly once a heartbeat has been confirmed and early screening is complete. The 12-week mark also typically brings some relief from first-trimester symptoms.\n\nBut 12 weeks is a convention, not a rule. There is no medical guideline that specifies when you must or should tell people.\n\n## Reasons to tell people earlier\n\n- You need practical support through difficult symptoms (severe nausea, hospitalisation)\n- You want people you trust to know in case of pregnancy loss, so you have support\n- Hiding the pregnancy in your daily life feels overwhelming or unsustainable\n- You work in a role where pregnancy affects safety and you need early adjustments\n\n## Reasons to wait\n\n- You prefer privacy until you feel more secure in the pregnancy\n- You want time to process the news yourselves first\n- You have experienced previous loss and want to manage your own feelings before managing others''\n\n## Who to tell first\n\nMany couples choose to tell their closest family or a best friend early \u2014 not because they plan to announce to everyone, but because they want support through the first trimester. This is different from a public announcement.\n\n## Navigating cultural expectations\n\nIn some cultural contexts, pregnancy announcements are surrounded by specific expectations \u2014 around timing, who should be told first, whether to share publicly on social media, or traditions around keeping the news quiet until a certain milestone. You do not have to follow any particular convention. Whatever approach respects your relationship with your pregnancy and the people in your life is the right one.\n\n## Telling your workplace\n\nYou are not legally required to tell your employer until a certain point in pregnancy (timing varies by country \u2014 typically around weeks 15\u201325 for formal notification). However, if your role involves physical demands, chemicals, radiation, or other occupational hazards, earlier disclosure allows you to request adjustments.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Your pregnancy announcement is personal and there is no single right approach.*',
 'relationships', 3, ARRAY['announcement','telling-people','first-trimester','workplace','cultural','privacy'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 8, 'Your First Prenatal Appointment: What to Expect and How to Prepare',
 'A guide to your booking appointment \u2014 what will happen, what to bring, and what questions to ask',
 E'## When your first appointment happens\n\nIn most health systems, your first formal prenatal appointment \u2014 often called the booking appointment \u2014 happens between weeks 8 and 12, though this varies. If you are registered with a GP or midwife service, contact them as soon as you have a positive pregnancy test to get on the schedule.\n\n## What happens at the booking appointment\n\nThis is typically a longer appointment (30\u201360 minutes). Expect:\n\n**Medical history review.** Your midwife or doctor will ask about your general health, any existing conditions, previous pregnancies, medications, family history, and lifestyle. Be honest \u2014 the information is used to plan your care, not to judge you.\n\n**Physical checks.** Blood pressure, weight and height (to calculate BMI), and urine testing. In some settings, an initial examination may be done.\n\n**Blood tests.** You will typically have blood drawn to check blood type and Rh factor, full blood count (anaemia check), immunity to rubella, syphilis screening, HIV screening (offered universally in many countries), hepatitis B status, and sometimes thyroid function.\n\n**Discussion of screening options.** Your provider will explain first trimester screening options, including the nuchal translucency scan and blood tests, and ask whether you want to proceed.\n\n**Your estimated due date.** Calculated from the date of your last menstrual period and confirmed by the dating scan.\n\n## What to bring\n\n- The date of your last menstrual period\n- List of any medications or supplements you are taking\n- Your medical history (significant conditions, surgeries, previous pregnancy details)\n- Your partner or support person, if you would like\n- Questions you have prepared in advance\n\n## Questions worth asking\n\n- What prenatal vitamins do you recommend?\n- What symptoms should prompt me to call between appointments?\n- When will my first scan be?\n- What screening tests are offered and what do they check for?\n- Are there any lifestyle adjustments you recommend for my specific situation?\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Antenatal care protocols vary between countries and providers. Your healthcare team will guide you through what is recommended in your context.*',
 'health', 4, ARRAY['first-appointment','booking-appointment','prenatal-care','first-trimester','antenatal'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

