('pregnancy', 6, 'Breast Changes in Pregnancy: What to Expect',
 'Why breasts change so early and so dramatically \u2014 and what helps',
 E'## Why breasts change in the first trimester\n\nBreast changes are often among the earliest signs of pregnancy, sometimes noticed even before a positive test. Rising levels of oestrogen and progesterone trigger significant structural changes in breast tissue as the body begins preparing for milk production months in advance.\n\n## What you might notice\n\n**Tenderness and sensitivity.** The breast tissue becomes highly sensitive, sometimes painfully so, especially in the early weeks. Even the pressure of clothing or a seatbelt can be uncomfortable.\n\n**Size increase.** Breasts typically begin increasing in size early in the first trimester, driven by an increase in glandular tissue and blood flow. This growth can be rapid and significant.\n\n**Visible veins.** As blood volume increases, veins beneath the skin may become more visible, appearing as blue or purple lines across the chest.\n\n**Changes to the nipple and areola.** The areola (the darker circle around the nipple) typically darkens and expands. Small bumps called Montgomery glands \u2014 sebaceous glands that lubricate the nipple \u2014 may become more prominent.\n\n**Colostrum leakage.** Some people begin producing and leaking small amounts of colostrum \u2014 the first milk \u2014 from the second trimester onward. This is normal and does not indicate a problem.\n\n## What helps\n\n**A well-fitting, supportive bra.** Your pre-pregnancy bras may no longer fit comfortably. A soft, supportive maternity or sports bra without underwire is often more comfortable during this period of rapid change. Getting professionally measured is worth the investment.\n\n**Sleeping in a soft bra.** Some people find wearing a soft bra at night reduces the discomfort of lying in different positions.\n\n**Gentle handling.** Communicate with your partner about sensitivity, particularly during intimacy.\n\nThese changes typically ease somewhat in the second trimester, though breasts continue to grow and prepare for feeding throughout pregnancy.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Contact your healthcare provider if you notice any lumps, unusual pain, or changes that concern you.*',
 'wellness', 3, ARRAY['breast-changes','first-trimester','body-changes','bra','tenderness','pregnancy-symptoms'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 7, 'Frequent Urination in Pregnancy: Why It Happens',
 'The bathroom trips no one warns you about \u2014 explained',
 E'## Why the bathroom becomes your most visited room\n\nNeeding to urinate frequently is one of the earliest and most persistent symptoms of pregnancy. It begins in the first trimester, often eases somewhat in the second, and returns with intensity in the third as the growing uterus presses directly on the bladder.\n\n## What causes it in the first trimester\n\n**Increased blood volume and kidney function.** Pregnancy triggers a dramatic increase in blood volume \u2014 eventually around 50% above pre-pregnancy levels. Your kidneys must filter this increased volume, producing significantly more urine.\n\n**hCG and progesterone.** These hormones influence kidney function and bladder sensitivity, contributing to the urge to urinate more often even before the uterus is large enough to press on the bladder.\n\n**Uterine position.** In the first trimester, the uterus sits low in the pelvis, very close to the bladder, and its growing size exerts early pressure.\n\n## What is normal\n\nGoing to the bathroom every 1\u20132 hours during waking hours is common. Waking once or twice overnight is also normal and increases as pregnancy progresses.\n\n## When to speak with your provider\n\nFrequent urination is normal. But certain symptoms alongside it are not:\n\n- Burning or stinging when you urinate\n- Cloudy or foul-smelling urine\n- Fever, chills, or back pain\n- Blood in urine\n\nThese symptoms may indicate a urinary tract infection (UTI), which is more common in pregnancy and requires treatment. Untreated UTIs in pregnancy can lead to kidney infections and preterm labour risk, so do not wait to get checked.\n\n## Practical management\n\nDo not restrict fluids to reduce urgency \u2014 staying well hydrated is essential in pregnancy. Instead, limit caffeinated drinks (which have a mild diuretic effect), void completely each time you urinate, and plan bathroom access around your daily routine.\n\nPelvic floor exercises (Kegels) support bladder control throughout pregnancy and recovery.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Contact your healthcare provider if you have any symptoms of a urinary tract infection.*',
 'health', 3, ARRAY['frequent-urination','first-trimester','bladder','uti','kidneys','pregnancy-symptoms'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 8, 'Constipation in Pregnancy: Causes and Safe Remedies',
 'One of the most common and least-discussed pregnancy symptoms \u2014 and how to manage it safely',
 E'## Why pregnancy causes constipation\n\nConstipation affects up to half of all pregnant people and can begin as early as the first trimester. The primary cause is progesterone, which relaxes smooth muscle throughout the body \u2014 including the muscles of the digestive tract. This slows the movement of food through the intestines, allowing more water to be absorbed from the stool, making it harder and more difficult to pass.\n\nIron supplementation (particularly iron sulfate, a common component of prenatal vitamins) worsens constipation for many people. The growing uterus also exerts increasing pressure on the bowel as pregnancy progresses.\n\n## Safe dietary approaches\n\n**Increase fibre gradually.** Aim for 25\u201330g of fibre per day from whole grains, fruits, vegetables, legumes, and nuts. Increase fibre gradually to avoid bloating and gas.\n\n**Drink plenty of water.** Fibre requires water to work effectively. Aim for at least 8\u201310 cups (2\u20132.5 litres) of fluid per day. Warm water in the morning can stimulate bowel movement.\n\n**Prunes and prune juice.** Contain sorbitol, a natural sugar that draws water into the bowel. Effective for many people.\n\n**Regular movement.** Even gentle walking supports bowel motility.\n\n## Safe treatments\n\n**Osmotic laxatives** (such as lactulose and macrogol/PEG) are considered safe in pregnancy and are often the first recommendation from healthcare providers when dietary measures are not sufficient.\n\n**Bulk-forming laxatives** (such as psyllium/ispaghula) are also safe and work by adding bulk to stool.\n\n**Stimulant laxatives** (such as senna or bisacodyl) are generally considered safe for short-term use in pregnancy but should be used under provider guidance.\n\n**Do not use** castor oil, mineral oil, or herbal laxatives without medical advice.\n\nIf constipation is severe, painful, or accompanied by rectal bleeding, contact your healthcare provider.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider before starting any laxative or supplement during pregnancy.*',
 'health', 4, ARRAY['constipation','first-trimester','digestion','fibre','progesterone','iron','prenatal-vitamins'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 7, 'Bloating and Gas in Pregnancy: Managing the Discomfort',
 'Why your digestive system slows down in pregnancy \u2014 and what gives relief',
 E'## The uncomfortable reality\n\nBloating, gas, and a feeling of abdominal fullness are extremely common in early pregnancy \u2014 and they often feel disproportionate to how early you are. Many people notice bloating before they have any bump at all.\n\n## Why it happens\n\nThe same progesterone that causes constipation also slows the entire digestive tract, giving the gut more time to ferment food and produce gas. The result is bloating, flatulence, and a distended, uncomfortable abdomen.\n\nCertain prenatal vitamins \u2014 particularly those containing iron \u2014 can worsen digestive symptoms. The uterus also begins to push on surrounding organs from relatively early, adding to the sensation of fullness.\n\n## Foods that tend to worsen bloating\n\n- Beans and lentils (though still nutritionally important \u2014 try smaller portions or canned varieties, which are better tolerated)\n- Cruciferous vegetables (broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower)\n- Carbonated drinks\n- High-fat foods\n- Onions and garlic\n- Artificial sweeteners\n\n## Strategies that help\n\n**Eat slowly and chew thoroughly.** Swallowing air while eating quickly contributes to gas.\n\n**Small, frequent meals.** Smaller portions are easier on a slower digestive system.\n\n**Stay active.** Gentle movement after meals helps move gas through the digestive tract.\n\n**Peppermint tea.** Can help ease intestinal spasms and gas. Check with your provider about safe herbal teas.\n\n**Probiotics.** Some evidence supports probiotic use for digestive symptoms in pregnancy. Speak with your provider about whether this is appropriate for you.\n\n**Adjust your prenatal vitamin timing.** Taking iron-containing vitamins with food rather than on an empty stomach can reduce gastrointestinal side effects.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Severe or worsening abdominal pain should always be assessed by a healthcare provider.*',
 'wellness', 3, ARRAY['bloating','gas','digestion','first-trimester','progesterone','pregnancy-symptoms'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 6, 'Headaches in the First Trimester: Causes and Safe Management',
 'Why headaches are common in early pregnancy and what you can safely take',
 E'## Why headaches are so common in early pregnancy\n\nHeadaches in the first trimester are reported by a significant proportion of pregnant people, and they often catch people off guard. Several factors converge to make them more likely:\n\n**Hormonal changes.** The rapid rise in oestrogen and progesterone affects blood vessel tone and can trigger headaches in people who are sensitive to hormonal fluctuation.\n\n**Increased blood volume.** As blood volume expands in early pregnancy, blood vessels must accommodate greater flow, which can contribute to headache.\n\n**Caffeine withdrawal.** Many people reduce or eliminate caffeine when they learn they are pregnant. For regular coffee or tea drinkers, this can trigger withdrawal headaches that can be quite severe in the first week of reduction.\n\n**Dehydration.** Nausea and vomiting reduce fluid intake, and dehydration is a common headache trigger.\n\n**Sleep disruption.** Poor sleep \u2014 from nausea, frequent urination, or anxiety \u2014 is a well-established headache trigger.\n\n**Low blood sugar.** Going too long without food causes blood sugar dips, a common headache driver.\n\n## What you can safely take\n\n**Paracetamol (acetaminophen)** is considered the safest over-the-counter pain reliever during pregnancy and can be used at the lowest effective dose for the shortest time needed.\n\n**Avoid ibuprofen, aspirin, and NSAIDs** unless specifically prescribed by your provider, particularly in the first trimester. These medications can affect fetal development.\n\n## Non-medication approaches\n\n- Rest in a quiet, dark room\n- Apply a cold or warm compress to the forehead or back of the neck\n- Stay hydrated \u2014 drink a large glass of water and rest\n- Eat a small snack if blood sugar may be low\n- Reduce gradually rather than stopping caffeine abruptly\n\n## When to seek urgent care\n\nHeadaches that are sudden and severe (the ''thunderclap'' type), accompanied by visual disturbances, swelling in the face or hands, or high blood pressure require immediate medical assessment as they can indicate preeclampsia.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Always consult your healthcare provider before taking any medication in pregnancy.*',
 'health', 4, ARRAY['headaches','first-trimester','paracetamol','caffeine','dehydration','pregnancy-symptoms'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 6, 'Mood Swings in the First Trimester: The Hormonal Reality',
 'Why your emotions feel amplified \u2014 and what to do when it becomes more than that',
 E'## Why emotions fluctuate so dramatically\n\nMood swings in early pregnancy are real, and they are driven by rapid, dramatic shifts in hormones \u2014 particularly oestrogen and progesterone, both of which influence brain chemistry. These hormones affect the same neurotransmitter systems that regulate mood, emotion, and stress response, including serotonin and GABA pathways.\n\nCombine this with physical exhaustion, nausea, disrupted sleep, and the psychological weight of a major life change, and it is entirely understandable that emotions feel harder to manage.\n\n## What is normal\n\nCrying at an advertisement. Feeling irritable about things that would not normally bother you. Swinging from excited to terrified in the same hour. Feeling weepy without a clear cause. These are common and do not indicate a mental health problem.\n\nMost people find mood symptoms improve significantly in the second trimester as hormones stabilise somewhat and the body adjusts.\n\n## When it is more than mood swings\n\nNot all emotional distress in pregnancy is simply hormonal. Anxiety and depression are genuinely more common during pregnancy than many people realise \u2014 affecting around 15\u201320% of pregnant people. Symptoms that warrant a conversation with your healthcare provider include:\n\n- Persistent low mood lasting more than two weeks\n- Inability to feel pleasure or look forward to things\n- Significant anxiety or worry that does not ease\n- Intrusive thoughts that feel distressing\n- Difficulty functioning at work or in daily life\n- Thoughts of harming yourself\n\nThese experiences are not a sign of weakness or failure, and they are treatable. Many people feel reluctant to raise mental health concerns in pregnancy, but your provider needs to know so they can support you.\n\n## What helps\n\n- Rest and physical care \u2014 fatigue amplifies emotional distress\n- Communicating with your partner or support person about what you are experiencing\n- Connecting with others who understand \u2014 whether friends, family, or peer support\n- Talking therapy, which is safe and effective in pregnancy\n- Mindfulness and relaxation practices\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If you are experiencing persistent low mood, anxiety, or any thoughts of self-harm, please speak with your healthcare provider.*',
 'mental-health', 4, ARRAY['mood-swings','first-trimester','hormones','emotions','anxiety','depression'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 4, 'What Is Safe to Eat in Pregnancy \u2014 and What to Avoid',
 'A clear, practical guide to the most important dietary rules in pregnancy',
 E'## The key principle\n\nPregnancy does not require an entirely different diet \u2014 it requires some specific adjustments to reduce risks that are particularly serious during fetal development. Most foods are completely safe. A relatively small list needs to be avoided or limited.\n\n## Foods to avoid\n\n**Raw or undercooked meat, poultry, and seafood.** Risk of Toxoplasma, Salmonella, Campylobacter, and other pathogens. Cook all meat until juices run clear and there is no pink flesh.\n\n**Raw shellfish.** Oysters, clams, and mussels eaten raw carry high Listeria and Vibrio risk. Cooked shellfish is safe.\n\n**High-mercury fish.** Shark, swordfish, king mackerel, tilefish, and bigeye tuna contain mercury levels that can impair fetal neurological development. Limit albacore (canned white) tuna to 1\u20132 servings per week. Low-mercury fish is safe and encouraged.\n\n**Unpasteurised dairy.** Raw milk and cheeses made from unpasteurised milk (brie, camembert, blue cheeses, queso fresco in some cases) carry Listeria risk.\n\n**Unpasteurised juices.** Fresh-pressed juices from juice bars may be unpasteurised. Check or opt for pasteurised.\n\n**Raw sprouts.** Alfalfa, bean, and clover sprouts are associated with Salmonella and E. coli outbreaks.\n\n**Deli meats and hot dogs.** Unless heated until steaming \u2014 Listeria risk.\n\n**Pate and liver products.** High in vitamin A as retinol, which is teratogenic at high doses. Avoid liver, liver pate, and cod liver oil supplements.\n\n**Alcohol.** No safe level has been established. The recommendation is to avoid it entirely.\n\n## Caffeine\n\nGuidelines suggest limiting to 200mg per day (roughly one 8oz filter coffee). Higher intake is associated with increased miscarriage risk and low birth weight.\n\n## What is safe\n\nThe vast majority of foods \u2014 including virtually all fruits, vegetables, grains, legumes, dairy (pasteurised), cooked meats, eggs (fully cooked), and low-mercury fish \u2014 are entirely safe and nutritionally valuable.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Guidelines may vary by country. Always consult your healthcare provider or a registered dietitian for personalised advice.*',
 'nutrition', 5, ARRAY['food-safety','diet','listeria','mercury','alcohol','caffeine','first-trimester'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 4, 'Medications in Pregnancy: What to Avoid and What Is Safe',
 'The essential guide to medication safety in the first trimester and beyond',
 E'## The basic rule\n\nNo medication \u2014 prescription or over-the-counter \u2014 should be taken during pregnancy without first checking that it is safe. This includes herbal supplements and remedies, which can be potent and are often inadequately tested in pregnancy.\n\nThat said, some medications are well-established as safe, and untreated medical conditions in pregnancy can be as harmful as the medications used to treat them. The goal is informed decision-making with your healthcare provider, not blanket avoidance.\n\n## Medications generally considered safe in pregnancy\n\n- **Paracetamol (acetaminophen):** For pain and fever. Use at the lowest effective dose for the shortest time.\n- **Certain antihistamines:** For allergies and nausea \u2014 your provider will advise on specific types.\n- **Most prenatal vitamins and folic acid**\n- **Many antibiotics:** Including amoxicillin and some cephalosporins, when prescribed for infection.\n\n## Medications to avoid or use with caution\n\n**NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen, aspirin):** Should generally be avoided, especially in the first trimester and after 20 weeks. Associated with increased miscarriage risk early on and fetal kidney and heart issues later.\n\n**Retinoids (Vitamin A derivatives):** Used for acne. Isotretinoin (Roaccutane) is highly teratogenic and causes severe birth defects. Do not use.\n\n**Tetracycline antibiotics:** Can affect bone and tooth development.\n\n**Some antidepressants, anti-epileptics, blood pressure medications, and blood thinners:** Some are safe; some carry risk. Never stop prescribed medications abruptly without medical guidance \u2014 the risk of uncontrolled illness is real.\n\n**Herbal supplements:** Many have not been studied in pregnancy and some have known risks. Avoid dong quai, black cohosh, blue cohosh, pennyroyal, and high-dose herbal preparations.\n\n## What to do\n\nCreate a full medication list and discuss each one with your provider at your first prenatal appointment. For ongoing prescriptions, your prescribing doctor should be aware of your pregnancy and can advise on safety or alternatives.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Never stop or change prescribed medications without consulting your healthcare provider.*',
 'safety', 4, ARRAY['medications','safety','first-trimester','ibuprofen','paracetamol','herbal','pregnancy'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 8, 'Travel in the First Trimester: What You Need to Know',
 'Whether it is safe to fly, drive, or travel internationally in the first trimester',
 E'## Is travel safe in the first trimester?\n\nFor most people with uncomplicated pregnancies, travel in the first trimester is safe. The main concerns are around comfort (nausea, fatigue, motion sickness), access to healthcare if needed, and a small number of specific risks depending on your destination.\n\n## Flying\n\nAir travel is considered safe in the first trimester. Commercial aircraft are pressurised to a level that does not pose a risk to the fetus. Most airlines allow travel up to 36 weeks without a medical certificate, though policies vary \u2014 check with your airline.\n\nOn longer flights:\n- Wear compression stockings \u2014 pregnancy increases DVT (blood clot) risk, and immobility during flights compounds this\n- Walk and stretch regularly (every 1\u20132 hours on long-haul flights)\n- Stay well hydrated\n- Sit in an aisle seat for easier bathroom access\n\n## Car travel\n\nLong car journeys are fine, but take regular breaks to move, stretch, and use the bathroom. Always wear a seatbelt \u2014 the lap belt should sit below the bump and the shoulder strap should run between the breasts.\n\n## Destinations to reconsider\n\n**Zika virus regions:** Zika is transmitted by mosquitoes and causes severe fetal brain malformations. Pregnant people should avoid destinations with active Zika transmission.\n\n**Malaria risk areas:** Some anti-malaria medications are not safe in pregnancy. If travel is essential, speak with a travel medicine specialist about the safest options.\n\n**High altitude destinations:** Limited evidence but some caution is advisable about very high altitudes above 3,500m in pregnancy.\n\n**Areas with limited healthcare access:** In the first trimester, when miscarriage risk is highest, being far from medical facilities is something to weigh.\n\n## Vaccinations for travel\n\nSome vaccines are safe in pregnancy; others are not. Live attenuated vaccines are generally avoided. Speak with a travel medicine clinic or your provider about what is safe before any travel with vaccination requirements.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Consult your healthcare provider before travelling, particularly internationally, during pregnancy.*',
 'safety', 4, ARRAY['travel','flying','first-trimester','zika','malaria','dvt','safety'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

