-- SECOND TRIMESTER: THE "HONEYMOON" PHASE
-- ============================================================

('pregnancy', 14, 'Welcome to the Second Trimester: What Changes Now',
 'Why weeks 14\u201327 feel so different \u2014 and what to look forward to and prepare for',
 E'## The shift in how you feel\n\nFor many people, crossing into the second trimester brings a marked improvement. Nausea eases for most by around weeks 12\u201314 as hCG levels plateau and begin to fall. Energy often returns. Appetite improves. The relentless first-trimester fog begins to lift.\n\nThis shift is not universal \u2014 some people continue to experience nausea well into the second trimester, and ongoing symptoms are not a sign that something is wrong. But statistically, the second trimester is the most comfortable phase of pregnancy for most people.\n\n## What is happening in your body\n\n- Your uterus has moved up out of the pelvis into the abdomen \u2014 you may start to notice a visible bump emerging\n- The placenta is fully functioning, taking over hormone production from the corpus luteum\n- Baby''s major organ systems are formed; the second trimester is largely about growth and refinement\n- You will begin to feel fetal movement \u2014 most people notice this for the first time between weeks 16 and 25\n- Your cardiovascular system is working significantly harder; blood volume continues to increase\n\n## Key appointments and milestones\n\n- **20-week anatomy scan:** The most detailed ultrasound of pregnancy, checking organ development in detail\n- **Glucose tolerance test:** Typically offered between weeks 24 and 28 to screen for gestational diabetes\n- **Ongoing blood pressure monitoring:** Preeclampsia monitoring becomes important from 20 weeks onward\n- **Second trimester blood tests** as recommended by your provider\n\n## What to start thinking about\n\nThe second trimester is often the right time to begin planning more concretely \u2014 childbirth education classes, setting up the nursery, beginning to think about feeding preferences, and discussing parental leave with your employer.\n\n## The psychological shift\n\nMany people feel more able to connect with the pregnancy in the second trimester \u2014 the risk of miscarriage has dropped significantly, there is often a visible bump, and movement begins. For others, anxiety does not simply switch off. Both experiences are valid.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider about what care and monitoring is recommended for your specific pregnancy.*',
 'wellness', 4, ARRAY['second-trimester','14-weeks','overview','milestones','bump','placenta'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 20, 'The 20-Week Anatomy Scan: What It Looks for and What to Expect',
 'The most detailed look at your baby during pregnancy \u2014 and what findings can mean',
 E'## What the anatomy scan is\n\nThe mid-pregnancy anatomy scan (also called the anomaly scan, morphology scan, or TIFFA scan) is typically performed between weeks 18 and 22. It is a detailed ultrasound examination that systematically checks the structure of your baby''s developing organs.\n\nUnlike the 12-week dating scan, this is primarily a health check, not just a size check. It takes longer \u2014 usually 30\u201345 minutes.\n\n## What the sonographer examines\n\n**Brain and skull.** Shape, midline structures, ventricles.\n\n**Face.** Checking for cleft lip (note: cleft palate is harder to see on ultrasound).\n\n**Heart.** Four-chamber view, major vessels entering and leaving the heart.\n\n**Spine.** Checking for spina bifida and other neural tube defects.\n\n**Abdominal wall and organs.** Stomach, kidneys, bladder, bowel.\n\n**Limbs.** Arms, legs, hands, feet.\n\n**Placenta.** Position (whether it is covering the cervix \u2014 placenta praevia), appearance.\n\n**Amniotic fluid.** Volume around the baby.\n\n**Cervical length.** In some settings, this is measured to assess preterm birth risk.\n\n## Finding out the sex\n\nIf you want to know the sex of your baby, this is the most reliable point to find out via ultrasound. The sonographer may be able to tell you, though accuracy depends on the baby''s position. Not all health systems offer this routinely \u2014 ask your provider beforehand.\n\n## If something unexpected is found\n\nAround 1\u20132% of scans identify a significant finding that requires follow-up. This might be a structural difference, a soft marker (an incidental finding associated with slightly higher chromosomal risk), or something that requires repeat imaging for confirmation.\n\nIf a finding is identified, you will typically be referred to a specialist \u2014 a maternal-fetal medicine specialist or a paediatric cardiologist, for example. Take time before making decisions. Ask for written information. Genetic counselling may be offered.\n\nMost markers on their own have low predictive value and many babies with soft markers on ultrasound are born completely healthy.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Your sonographer and healthcare provider will explain any findings from your specific scan.*',
 'health', 5, ARRAY['20-week-scan','anatomy-scan','anomaly-scan','second-trimester','ultrasound','morphology'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 18, 'Feeling Your Baby Move: What It Feels Like and When to Expect It',
 'First movements are one of pregnancy''s most powerful moments \u2014 here is what to know',
 E'## When to expect first movements\n\nFirst fetal movements \u2014 called quickening \u2014 are typically felt between weeks 16 and 25. First-time parents tend to notice them later (closer to 20\u201325 weeks) because the sensation is unfamiliar and easy to misinterpret. Those who have been pregnant before may notice movement earlier because they recognise what they are feeling.\n\nThe position of your placenta also matters. An anterior placenta (one that lies on the front wall of the uterus) acts as a cushion between you and your baby, dampening the sensation. If you have an anterior placenta, you may not feel clear movements until week 24 or later, which is completely normal.\n\n## What it feels like\n\nThe earliest movements are subtle and often described as:\n\n- Fluttering, like butterflies in the stomach\n- Bubbles popping from inside\n- A gentle tapping or knocking\n- Rolling or swooshing sensations\n\nAs the baby grows and movements become stronger, you will feel more definite kicks, rolls, jabs, and what feels like hiccups (a rhythmic, repetitive movement).\n\n## When movement becomes regular\n\nBy around weeks 24\u201328, most people begin to notice more consistent movement patterns. Your baby has periods of sleep (which can last 20\u201340 minutes) and periods of activity. Over time you will begin to recognise your baby''s pattern \u2014 more active at certain times of day, more active after you eat or drink something cold.\n\n## Movement awareness\n\nFrom around 28 weeks, many providers recommend awareness of fetal movement \u2014 not necessarily formal kick counting, but a general awareness of what is normal for your baby. If movement is significantly reduced or absent, contact your healthcare provider or maternity unit promptly. Do not wait until the next day.\n\nIn the second trimester, before movement is established as a regular pattern, sudden absence of movement is less concerning than later in pregnancy, but any significant concern about change in movement is worth raising with your provider.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Always contact your healthcare provider if you are concerned about changes in your baby''s movement.*',
 'development', 4, ARRAY['fetal-movement','quickening','second-trimester','kicks','anterior-placenta','milestones'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 16, 'Round Ligament Pain: What It Is and How to Manage It',
 'The sharp twinge in your lower abdomen or groin \u2014 what causes it and whether to be concerned',
 E'## What is round ligament pain?\n\nThe round ligaments are two thick bands of tissue that run from either side of the uterus down through the groin to the labia. During pregnancy, as the uterus grows and changes position, these ligaments must stretch and elongate to support the expanding weight.\n\nRound ligament pain is the sharp, stabbing, or aching pain that results from this stretching \u2014 typically felt in the lower abdomen, groin, or upper inner thigh on one or both sides.\n\n## When it typically appears\n\nRound ligament pain usually begins in the second trimester, most commonly between weeks 14 and 22, when the uterus is growing rapidly enough to put the ligaments under significant tension.\n\n## What it feels like\n\nMost people describe it as a sudden, sharp shooting pain lasting only seconds, often triggered by a specific movement \u2014 getting up from a chair, rolling over in bed, sneezing, coughing, or laughing. Some people experience a duller, achy sensation that can last minutes to hours.\n\n## What helps\n\n**Slow down your movements.** The pain is most often triggered by sudden movements. Getting up slowly, bracing before a sneeze, and rolling over in stages rather than in one motion can reduce the trigger.\n\n**Support your bump.** A maternity support belt can help distribute the weight of the uterus and reduce ligament tension.\n\n**Prenatal yoga and stretching.** Gentle hip flexor stretches and prenatal yoga poses can help.\n\n**Heat.** A warm pack on the affected area can ease discomfort.\n\n**Rest.** If the pain is persistent or achy rather than sudden, resting with a pillow supporting the bump may help.\n\n## When to seek care\n\nRound ligament pain is generally harmless, but not all lower abdominal pain in pregnancy is round ligament pain. Contact your provider if:\n\n- Pain is severe, constant, or worsening\n- Pain is accompanied by fever, chills, bleeding, or unusual discharge\n- You have any doubt about what is causing it\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If you have any concerns about abdominal pain during pregnancy, contact your healthcare provider.*',
 'health', 3, ARRAY['round-ligament-pain','second-trimester','abdominal-pain','pregnancy-symptoms','uterus'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 26, 'Glucose Tolerance Test (GTT): Gestational Diabetes Screening Explained',
 'What the test involves, how to prepare, and what your results mean',
 E'## What is the glucose tolerance test?\n\nThe glucose tolerance test (GTT) \u2014 also called the oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) \u2014 is a screening test for gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM). It is typically offered between weeks 24 and 28 in most pregnancy guidelines, though women with certain risk factors may be screened earlier.\n\n## Who is offered screening\n\nUniversal screening is offered in many countries. In others, screening is targeted at people with risk factors including:\n\n- BMI above 30\n- Previous gestational diabetes\n- Baby in a previous pregnancy weighing over 4.5kg\n- Family history of type 2 diabetes\n- South Asian, Middle Eastern, African, or Caribbean ethnicity (higher prevalence in these populations)\n- Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)\n\n## What the test involves\n\n**The full GTT (2-hour test):** You fast overnight (typically 8\u201312 hours). A fasting blood sample is taken. You drink a glucose solution (usually 75g of glucose dissolved in water). Blood is taken again at 1 hour and 2 hours after the drink.\n\n**The 1-hour glucose challenge test:** Used as an initial screen in some countries (particularly the US). No fasting required. If the 1-hour result is above threshold, a full GTT follows.\n\n## How to prepare\n\nFast from the previous evening \u2014 water only. Avoid strenuous exercise the morning of the test. Take your medications as normal unless told otherwise. Plan to be at the clinic or lab for 2\u20133 hours. Bring a snack to eat after the test.\n\n## What results mean\n\nThresholds vary between guidelines. A common standard is:\n\n- Fasting glucose at or above 5.1 mmol/L, OR\n- 1-hour glucose at or above 10.0 mmol/L, OR\n- 2-hour glucose at or above 8.5 mmol/L\n\nMeeting any one of these thresholds typically leads to a diagnosis of gestational diabetes. Your healthcare team will explain the specific thresholds used by your service.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Your healthcare provider will interpret your results in the context of your full clinical picture.*',
 'health', 4, ARRAY['gtt','glucose-tolerance-test','gestational-diabetes','second-trimester','screening','gdm'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 26, 'Gestational Diabetes: Diagnosis, Management, and Outlook',
 'What a GDM diagnosis means, how it is managed, and what to expect for your pregnancy and beyond',
 E'## What is gestational diabetes?\n\nGestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) is a form of diabetes that develops during pregnancy. It occurs when pregnancy hormones (particularly human placental lactogen and progesterone) cause insulin resistance \u2014 meaning your cells respond less efficiently to insulin \u2014 and your pancreas cannot compensate by producing enough extra insulin to maintain normal blood sugar levels.\n\nGDM affects around 5\u201310% of pregnancies globally, with higher rates in certain ethnic groups. It is not caused by eating too much sugar.\n\n## Risks if unmanaged\n\nElevated blood sugar levels affect both mother and baby. Uncontrolled GDM can lead to:\n\n- Baby growing larger than normal (macrosomia), increasing risk of birth complications\n- Higher likelihood of caesarean section\n- Neonatal hypoglycaemia (low blood sugar in the baby after birth)\n- Premature birth\n- Increased risk of the mother developing type 2 diabetes in later life\n\nWith appropriate management, the vast majority of people with GDM have uncomplicated pregnancies and healthy babies.\n\n## How it is managed\n\n**Blood glucose monitoring.** You will be given a glucometer and shown how to test your blood sugar at home \u2014 typically fasting and after meals.\n\n**Dietary changes.** A dietitian will help you plan a diet that manages blood sugar: spreading carbohydrates evenly across meals, choosing lower glycaemic index foods, balancing meals with protein and healthy fats. This does not mean eliminating carbohydrates or cultural foods \u2014 it means managing portions and combinations.\n\n**Physical activity.** Gentle activity after meals (a 15-minute walk, for example) significantly improves insulin sensitivity and blood glucose response.\n\n**Medication.** If blood sugar targets cannot be met with diet and activity alone, metformin or insulin injections may be recommended. Both are safe in pregnancy.\n\n## After birth\n\nGDM resolves in most people after delivery. A glucose test is recommended at 6\u201312 weeks postpartum to confirm this. Lifetime risk of developing type 2 diabetes is elevated, making long-term lifestyle maintenance important.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. A GDM diagnosis should be managed in partnership with your healthcare team including your obstetrician, midwife, and dietitian.*',
 'health', 5, ARRAY['gestational-diabetes','gdm','blood-sugar','insulin','second-trimester','diet','management'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 22, 'Preeclampsia: Signs to Watch for and When to Seek Help',
 'Understanding one of the most important pregnancy complications \u2014 and how early recognition saves lives',
 E'## What is preeclampsia?\n\nPreeclampsia is a pregnancy complication characterised by high blood pressure (hypertension) combined with signs that indicate involvement of other organ systems, most commonly the kidneys (signalled by protein in the urine). It typically develops after 20 weeks of pregnancy.\n\nIt affects around 2\u20138% of pregnancies worldwide and is a leading cause of maternal and perinatal mortality globally. Early recognition and monitoring are critical.\n\n## Who is at higher risk?\n\nRisk factors include:\n- First pregnancy\n- Previous preeclampsia\n- Multiple pregnancy (twins or more)\n- Pre-existing high blood pressure, kidney disease, or diabetes\n- Obesity\n- Family history of preeclampsia\n- Age over 40\n- Autoimmune conditions such as lupus\n\nPeople with multiple risk factors may be offered low-dose aspirin from early in pregnancy (typically week 12) as a preventive measure \u2014 evidence supports its effectiveness in reducing preeclampsia risk.\n\n## Warning signs to know\n\n**High blood pressure.** Defined in pregnancy as 140/90 mmHg or higher on two readings. This is measured at every prenatal appointment for this reason.\n\n**Severe headache** that does not respond to paracetamol.\n\n**Visual disturbances.** Blurring, flashing lights, seeing spots.\n\n**Swelling.** Significant swelling of the face, hands, or feet \u2014 though note that some ankle swelling is normal in pregnancy.\n\n**Upper abdominal pain** (right upper quadrant \u2014 under the ribs on the right side). Can indicate liver involvement.\n\n**Sudden weight gain** from fluid retention.\n\n## What to do\n\nIf you experience any of the above \u2014 particularly headache, visual changes, or upper abdominal pain \u2014 do not wait for your next scheduled appointment. Contact your midwife or maternity unit immediately. These symptoms can escalate rapidly.\n\nThe only cure for preeclampsia is delivery of the baby and placenta. Management before this point focuses on monitoring, blood pressure control, and timing delivery safely.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Preeclampsia is a medical emergency when severe. If you have any of the warning signs described, seek medical care immediately.*',
 'safety', 5, ARRAY['preeclampsia','blood-pressure','hypertension','second-trimester','warning-signs','aspirin'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 16, 'Iron Deficiency in Pregnancy: Symptoms, Diet, and Supplements',
 'Why iron needs increase dramatically in pregnancy and how to meet them',
 E'## Why pregnancy depletes iron\n\nIron is essential for making haemoglobin \u2014 the protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen. During pregnancy, your blood volume increases by around 50% to supply your baby and placenta, and you need significantly more iron to produce the extra haemoglobin required.\n\nIron needs increase from around 18mg per day before pregnancy to 27mg per day during pregnancy. Iron deficiency is the most common nutrient deficiency in pregnancy worldwide.\n\n## Symptoms of iron deficiency\n\nMild deficiency may cause no obvious symptoms. As deficiency progresses:\n\n- Fatigue (beyond normal pregnancy tiredness)\n- Breathlessness on minimal exertion\n- Palpitations\n- Pale skin, pale inner eyelids or gums\n- Dizziness or lightheadedness\n- Difficulty concentrating\n\nA blood test (full blood count) confirms anaemia. Your haemoglobin and ferritin (iron stores) will be measured at booking and again in the third trimester in most antenatal care protocols.\n\n## Dietary sources of iron\n\n**Haem iron (animal sources \u2014 more easily absorbed):** Red meat, lamb, beef, liver (limited in pregnancy due to vitamin A), chicken, fish.\n\n**Non-haem iron (plant and fortified sources):** Lentils, chickpeas, black beans, kidney beans, tofu, tempeh, dark leafy greens (spinach, kale, bok choy), quinoa, fortified cereals, pumpkin seeds, dried apricots.\n\n**Boost absorption:** Eat iron-rich foods alongside vitamin C (tomatoes, peppers, citrus, strawberries). Avoid tea and coffee with iron-rich meals as tannins reduce absorption.\n\n## Supplementation\n\nMost prenatal vitamins contain iron. If anaemia is diagnosed, your provider may prescribe additional iron supplementation. Common side effects include constipation and dark stools \u2014 discuss alternatives with your provider if this is significant for you.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Iron supplementation should be taken under healthcare provider guidance. Do not self-supplement at high doses without testing.*',
 'nutrition', 4, ARRAY['iron','anaemia','second-trimester','nutrition','supplements','haemoglobin','diet'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 16, 'Heartburn and Acid Reflux in Pregnancy: Causes and Management',
 'Why heartburn becomes almost universal in the second and third trimesters \u2014 and safe ways to get relief',
 E'## Why heartburn is so common in pregnancy\n\nHeartburn affects a majority of pregnant people, and it tends to worsen as pregnancy progresses. Two main factors drive it:\n\n**Progesterone relaxes the lower oesophageal sphincter.** This muscle normally acts as a valve, keeping stomach acid in the stomach. Progesterone''s relaxing effect on smooth muscle means the sphincter works less efficiently, allowing acid to escape upward into the oesophagus.\n\n**The growing uterus compresses the stomach.** As the uterus grows from the second trimester onward, it increasingly pushes upward against the stomach, reducing its capacity and increasing pressure on the sphincter.\n\n## Dietary and lifestyle approaches\n\n- Eat smaller, more frequent meals \u2014 large meals increase stomach pressure\n- Avoid lying down for 1\u20132 hours after eating\n- Elevate the head of your bed slightly (raising the mattress head by 15\u201320cm)\n- Avoid spicy, fatty, fried, and acidic foods (tomatoes, citrus, coffee, chocolate, carbonated drinks) \u2014 though triggers are individual\n- Eat slowly and chew thoroughly\n- Wear loose, comfortable clothing around the abdomen\n\n## Safe medications in pregnancy\n\n**Antacids (calcium carbonate, magnesium hydroxide):** Generally considered safe for occasional use. Avoid antacids containing sodium bicarbonate or magnesium trisilicate.\n\n**Alginate-containing antacids (e.g. Gaviscon):** Form a protective layer on top of stomach contents, helping prevent reflux. Widely recommended in pregnancy.\n\n**H2 blockers (ranitidine, famotidine):** Considered safe in pregnancy when antacids are insufficient.\n\n**Proton pump inhibitors (omeprazole, pantoprazole):** Used when other measures fail. Generally considered safe but ideally used under provider guidance.\n\nAlways check with your provider or pharmacist before taking any medication in pregnancy.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Persistent or severe heartburn should be discussed with your healthcare provider.*',
 'health', 4, ARRAY['heartburn','acid-reflux','second-trimester','gerd','antacids','digestion','progesterone'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 18, 'Back Pain in Pregnancy: Safe Exercises and Relief Strategies',
 'Why back pain is so common in pregnancy and evidence-based ways to find relief',
 E'## Why pregnancy causes back pain\n\nBack pain affects 50\u201380% of pregnant people at some point, most commonly from the second trimester onward. Multiple factors converge:\n\n**Postural changes.** As the uterus grows forward, the centre of gravity shifts. The lower back arches (increasing lumbar lordosis) to compensate, placing strain on the lumbar and sacral muscles and joints.\n\n**Relaxin hormone.** Relaxin loosens ligaments throughout the body in preparation for birth \u2014 a necessary change for the pelvis, but one that also reduces stability in the sacroiliac joints and contributes to lower back and pelvic girdle pain.\n\n**Weight increase.** The added weight of the growing uterus, placenta, amniotic fluid, increased blood volume, and breast tissue creates significant load on the spine.\n\n**Abdominal muscle separation (diastasis recti).** The abdominal muscles stretch and may begin to separate, reducing core support for the spine.\n\n## Strategies that help\n\n**Pelvic floor and core exercises.** Gentle core strengthening that does not involve crunches or sit-ups supports spinal stability. Pelvic floor exercises also support pelvic girdle pain.\n\n**Prenatal yoga and Pilates.** Both are effective for pregnancy back pain when taught by instructors qualified to work with pregnant people.\n\n**Swimming and water-based exercise.** The buoyancy of water reduces load on the spine while allowing full movement \u2014 many people find aqua exercise the most comfortable form of exercise in the second half of pregnancy.\n\n**Heat and cold therapy.** Warm packs on aching muscles are safe and effective for relief.\n\n**Supportive footwear.** Flat, supportive shoes reduce the postural compensation pattern that worsens back pain. Avoid high heels.\n\n**Sleep positioning.** Sleeping on your side with a pillow between your knees and one under your bump reduces spinal strain.\n\n**Physiotherapy.** A physiotherapist specialised in pelvic health can assess and treat pregnancy-related back and pelvic pain with specific techniques including manual therapy, postural advice, and tailored exercise.\n\n**Maternity support belt.** Can help distribute uterine weight.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Persistent, severe, or neurological back pain (pain radiating down the leg, weakness, or numbness) should be assessed by a healthcare provider.*',
 'wellness', 5, ARRAY['back-pain','second-trimester','pelvic-girdle-pain','exercise','physiotherapy','posture'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 20, 'Sleep in the Second Trimester: Positioning and Common Issues',
 'Why sleep changes in the second trimester and how to get the rest you need',
 E'## Sleep in the second trimester: the mixed picture\n\nThe second trimester often brings some relief from the extreme first-trimester fatigue and nausea that make sleep difficult. Many people sleep better in the second trimester than they did in the first or will in the third. But new sleep challenges emerge.\n\n## Why back sleeping becomes discouraged\n\nFrom around 20 weeks, most providers advise sleeping on your side rather than your back. When you lie flat on your back, the weight of the growing uterus compresses the inferior vena cava \u2014 the large vein that returns blood to the heart from the lower body. This can reduce blood flow and cause dizziness, shortness of breath, or low blood pressure.\n\n**Left side sleeping** is commonly recommended because it maximises blood flow to the placenta, though right side sleeping is also safe. If you wake on your back, do not panic \u2014 simply roll back to your side.\n\n## Common second-trimester sleep issues\n\n**Leg cramps.** Sudden, painful muscle cramps in the calf or foot, often at night, are very common. Stretching the calf before bed, staying well hydrated, and ensuring adequate calcium and magnesium intake may help. Speak with your provider about magnesium supplementation if cramps are frequent.\n\n**Restless legs syndrome.** An uncomfortable urge to move the legs, often worse at rest and in the evenings. Associated with iron deficiency in pregnancy \u2014 have your levels checked.\n\n**Increasing difficulty getting comfortable.** As the bump grows, finding a comfortable position requires more pillows. A full-length pregnancy pillow is a worthwhile investment from the second trimester.\n\n**Vivid dreams.** Hormonal changes and altered sleep architecture during pregnancy produce vivid, often strange, and sometimes disturbing dreams. This is normal.\n\n**Frequent urination overnight.** Ongoing throughout pregnancy.\n\n## Practical tips\n\n- Use pillows to support your bump, between your knees, and behind your back\n- Establish a calming bedtime routine\n- Avoid screens for 30\u201360 minutes before bed\n- Keep the bedroom cool and dark\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Discuss persistent sleep problems with your healthcare provider.*',
 'sleep', 4, ARRAY['sleep','second-trimester','side-sleeping','leg-cramps','restless-legs','positioning'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 18, 'Sex During Pregnancy: Safety, Positions, and When to Avoid It',
 'An honest guide to intimacy during pregnancy \u2014 what is safe and what changes',
 E'## Is sex safe during pregnancy?\n\nFor most people with uncomplicated pregnancies, sex is completely safe throughout pregnancy \u2014 including the second trimester. The baby is cushioned by the amniotic sac and surrounded by amniotic fluid. The cervix is sealed by the mucus plug. Orgasm and normal penetrative sex do not cause miscarriage in healthy pregnancies.\n\nMany couples find the second trimester a comfortable time for intimacy. Nausea has often eased, energy has returned, and the bump is not yet large enough to make movement difficult.\n\n## Physical changes that affect intimacy\n\nIncreased blood flow to the pelvic area can heighten sensitivity and arousal for some people, making sex more pleasurable. For others, pelvic pressure, tenderness, or general discomfort reduces desire or comfort. Both responses are normal.\n\nSpotting after sex is common due to the increased vascularity of the cervix \u2014 it is usually harmless, but mention it to your provider if it is concerning.\n\n## Comfortable positions\n\nAs the bump grows, some positions become less comfortable. Experimenting with positions where penetration is shallower and the bump is not compressed tends to work better \u2014 for example side-lying, with the pregnant partner on top, or from behind. Open communication with your partner about what is comfortable is essential.\n\n## When to avoid sex or seek advice first\n\nSpeak with your provider before having sex if you have:\n\n- Placenta praevia (placenta covering the cervix) \u2014 penetrative sex is typically advised against\n- A history of preterm labour or cervical incompetence\n- Unexplained vaginal bleeding\n- Premature rupture of membranes (waters broken)\n\n## Desire changes\n\nIt is entirely normal for libido to fluctuate throughout pregnancy \u2014 increasing in some people, decreasing in others, or varying week to week. Desire discrepancy between partners is common. Communication, non-sexual intimacy, and mutual support are as important as sexual activity itself.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If you have any concerns about sex during your specific pregnancy, speak with your healthcare provider.*',
 'relationships', 4, ARRAY['sex','intimacy','second-trimester','safety','libido','positions','relationships'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 16, 'Exercise in Pregnancy: What Is Safe and What to Avoid',
 'Evidence-based guidance on staying active safely through the second trimester',
 E'## Why exercise in pregnancy is beneficial\n\nRegular moderate exercise during pregnancy is associated with significant benefits including reduced risk of gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, preterm birth, and excessive gestational weight gain. It supports mood, sleep, back pain management, and recovery after birth. Exercise does not increase miscarriage risk in uncomplicated pregnancies.\n\nThe American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, and equivalent bodies worldwide recommend 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic activity per week for pregnant people without contraindications.\n\n## Safe activities in the second trimester\n\n- Walking (accessible and effective)\n- Swimming and aqua aerobics\n- Stationary cycling\n- Prenatal yoga and Pilates (with a qualified instructor)\n- Low-impact aerobics\n- Modified strength training (avoiding lying flat on your back from 20 weeks)\n- Dancing\n\nIf you were active before pregnancy, you can generally continue your usual activities with modifications. The second trimester is not the time to begin an intense new training programme, but maintaining existing fitness is beneficial.\n\n## What to modify or avoid\n\n**Avoid:** Contact sports, activities with fall risk (cycling on roads, horse riding, skiing, gymnastics), high-altitude activities above 3,500m, scuba diving, hot yoga or hot Pilates (overheating poses risks in pregnancy).\n\n**Avoid lying flat on your back** for exercise from around 20 weeks.\n\n**Reduce intensity if needed.** A simple guide: you should be able to hold a conversation during exercise. If you are too breathless to speak, you are working too hard.\n\n## Warning signs to stop and seek advice\n\nStop exercising and contact your provider if you experience: vaginal bleeding, dizziness or feeling faint, chest pain, shortness of breath before exertion, painful contractions, or reduced fetal movement.\n\n## Pelvic floor exercises\n\nThese should be part of every pregnant person''s routine. Kegel exercises \u2014 contracting and releasing the pelvic floor muscles \u2014 support bladder control, pelvic organ support, and postpartum recovery.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If you have any pregnancy complications or uncertainties about what exercise is safe for you, consult your healthcare provider.*',
 'wellness', 4, ARRAY['exercise','fitness','second-trimester','walking','swimming','prenatal-yoga','pelvic-floor'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 20, 'Skin Changes in Pregnancy: Stretch Marks, Linea Nigra, and More',
 'The visible skin changes of pregnancy \u2014 what causes them and what you can and cannot do about them',
 E'## Why skin changes in pregnancy\n\nHormonal shifts, increased blood volume, and the physical stretching of tissue all cause visible changes to the skin during pregnancy. Most are harmless and temporary, though some persist after delivery.\n\n## Stretch marks (striae gravidarum)\n\nStretch marks are one of the most common pregnancy skin changes, affecting around 50\u201390% of pregnant people. They occur when the skin is stretched faster than the collagen fibres can accommodate, causing micro-tears that appear as red, pink, purple, or silvery streaks \u2014 most commonly on the abdomen, breasts, thighs, and buttocks.\n\nThe primary determinant of whether you get stretch marks is genetics \u2014 if your mother had them, your likelihood increases. Hydration and skin moisturisation may support skin elasticity, but no cream or oil has been definitively proven to prevent stretch marks. However, keeping skin hydrated does not hurt and may reduce itching from skin stretching.\n\nAfter delivery, stretch marks typically fade to silver or skin-toned streaks but do not disappear completely.\n\n## Linea nigra\n\nThe linea nigra (''dark line'') is a pigmented line that runs from the navel to the pubic area. It is caused by hormonal stimulation of melanin-producing cells and typically appears from around the second trimester. It is harmless and fades after delivery, usually within a few months.\n\n## Melasma (chloasma, the ''mask of pregnancy'')\n\nPatches of darker pigmentation on the face \u2014 particularly on the forehead, cheeks, and upper lip \u2014 are caused by increased melanin production stimulated by pregnancy hormones. Sun exposure worsens it significantly. Daily SPF use from early pregnancy can reduce severity. It typically fades postpartum, though it can take months.\n\n## Itching\n\nMild itching as the skin stretches is common and normal. Moisturising regularly can help. However, **intense or generalised itching \u2014 particularly on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet at night \u2014 must be reported to your provider**, as it can be a symptom of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (ICP), a liver condition that requires monitoring and management.\n\n## Other common skin changes\n\nIncreased oiliness or acne (driven by androgens), vascular spider veins and broken capillaries, and darkening of existing moles and freckles are all common. Any mole that changes in colour, shape, or size should be evaluated by a dermatologist.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Persistent or severe skin symptoms should be discussed with your healthcare provider.*',
 'wellness', 4, ARRAY['stretch-marks','linea-nigra','melasma','skin','second-trimester','itching','cholestasis'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 16, 'Dental Care in Pregnancy: Why It Matters and What to Do',
 'Pregnancy changes your mouth as well as your body \u2014 and dental health directly affects pregnancy outcomes',
 E'## The pregnancy-oral health connection\n\nDental health during pregnancy is not a cosmetic issue \u2014 it is a genuine health concern. Research consistently shows links between gum disease (periodontitis) and increased risks of preterm birth and low birth weight, though the mechanisms are still being studied. Good oral health during pregnancy matters for both you and your baby.\n\n## Pregnancy gingivitis\n\nUp to 70% of pregnant people develop gingivitis \u2014 inflammation of the gums \u2014 during pregnancy. This is primarily caused by increased progesterone, which amplifies the gum tissue''s response to plaque bacteria. Signs include red, swollen, and bleeding gums, especially when brushing.\n\nPregnancy gingivitis typically resolves after delivery, but left unmanaged it can progress to periodontitis (deeper gum disease).\n\n## Is dental treatment safe in pregnancy?\n\nYes. Routine dental care \u2014 check-ups, cleaning, and most treatments \u2014 is safe during pregnancy. Many people avoid the dentist during pregnancy out of concern, which is a mistake.\n\n- **Dental X-rays:** Can be taken during pregnancy when needed, with appropriate abdominal shielding. The dose of radiation is minimal.\n- **Local anaesthesia:** Lidocaine is safe in pregnancy.\n- **Elective cosmetic procedures:** Can wait until after delivery.\n- The second trimester is generally the most comfortable time for any necessary dental work.\n\n## Practical oral care in pregnancy\n\n- Brush twice daily with fluoride toothpaste\n- Floss daily\n- Attend regular dental check-ups \u2014 inform your dentist you are pregnant\n- If morning sickness causes vomiting, rinse your mouth with water or a fluoride mouthwash afterward, and wait 30\u201360 minutes before brushing to avoid brushing acid onto softened enamel\n- Watch sugar intake, as pregnancy cravings for sweet foods increase cavity risk\n\nTell your dentist you are pregnant and how far along you are \u2014 they can adjust treatment timing and choices accordingly.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with both your dentist and obstetrician about any dental concerns during pregnancy.*',
 'health', 3, ARRAY['dental','oral-health','gingivitis','second-trimester','teeth','gum-disease'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 18, 'Mental Health in the Second Trimester: The Calmer Phase That Is Not Always Calm',
 'Why anxiety and depression do not simply switch off when physical symptoms ease',
 E'## The expectation vs reality gap\n\nThe second trimester is widely described as the honeymoon phase of pregnancy \u2014 nausea eases, energy returns, a bump emerges. The cultural narrative is one of blossoming and enjoying. And for some people, this is genuinely their experience.\n\nBut for others, the second trimester brings its own emotional weight. Anxiety does not automatically ease when symptoms improve. Depression can emerge at any point in pregnancy. And the pressure to feel happy and grateful when you are struggling can be its own burden.\n\nAround 15\u201320% of pregnant people experience clinically significant anxiety or depression. These are not character failures. They are health conditions with effective treatments.\n\n## Why the second trimester can still be hard\n\nThe 20-week anatomy scan is a significant source of anxiety for many people \u2014 the fear of an unexpected finding can be overwhelming. For people who have experienced pregnancy loss, passing the point of a previous loss does not erase hypervigilance. For those with a history of anxiety or depression, pregnancy hormones can exacerbate underlying vulnerabilities.\n\nLife circumstances \u2014 relationship stress, financial concerns, work pressures, unsupportive environments \u2014 do not pause for pregnancy.\n\n## What to watch for\n\n- Persistent low mood or inability to feel pleasure, lasting more than two weeks\n- Excessive or uncontrollable worry about your pregnancy, baby, or future\n- Panic attacks\n- Intrusive thoughts (unwanted, distressing thoughts about the baby''s safety, or your own)\n- Withdrawing from people and activities\n- Difficulty functioning in daily life\n\n## What helps\n\nTalking therapy \u2014 particularly cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) and mindfulness-based approaches \u2014 is effective and safe in pregnancy. Medication is also an option for some people; speak with your provider about the risk-benefit picture for your specific situation.\n\nDo not wait until things feel unmanageable. Raising concerns with your midwife or GP at any routine appointment is appropriate and important.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If you are experiencing mental health difficulties in pregnancy, please speak with your healthcare provider. If you have thoughts of harming yourself, contact emergency services or a crisis line immediately.*',
 'mental-health', 4, ARRAY['mental-health','anxiety','depression','second-trimester','wellbeing','talking-therapy'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 22, 'Preparing Your Workplace for Maternity Leave: Practical Steps',
 'When to tell your employer, what your rights are, and how to set yourself up for a smooth transition',
 E'## When you need to tell your employer\n\nLegal notification requirements vary by country. In the UK, for example, you must notify your employer of your pregnancy and intended leave start date at least 15 weeks before your due date (around week 25). In the US, there is no federal requirement, though notifying earlier allows for planning and any necessary workplace adjustments.\n\nYou do not need to disclose your pregnancy before then, but earlier disclosure may be in your interest if your role involves physical demands, exposure to hazards, or if you need time off for appointments.\n\n## Know your rights\n\nEmployment rights during pregnancy typically include (though specifics vary by country):\n\n- Protection against discrimination and dismissal because of pregnancy\n- Paid time off for antenatal appointments\n- Entitlement to maternity leave and pay (amounts and duration vary significantly)\n- The right to request workplace adjustments (risk assessment for your role)\n- Protection while on leave\n\nResearch your local employment law and your employer''s specific maternity policy \u2014 entitlements can exceed the legal minimum. HR is a useful starting point.\n\n## Practical preparation for handover\n\nStart planning your handover early \u2014 ideally at least 2\u20133 months before your leave start date:\n\n- Document your ongoing projects, contacts, and processes\n- Identify who will cover key responsibilities\n- Brief your manager on pending decisions and deadlines\n- Set expectations for coverage of your role \u2014 and what you will and will not be available for during leave\n\n## Managing the workplace response\n\nPregnancy announcements in the workplace are received in many different ways. If you encounter unwanted comments, intrusive questions, or changes to your responsibilities that feel unfair, document them and speak with HR. Pregnancy discrimination is illegal in most countries.\n\nDecide in advance what you will and will not share about your pregnancy at work, and set boundaries that feel right for you.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Employment rights vary significantly by country and individual employment contracts. Seek professional legal or HR advice for your specific situation.*',
 'wellness', 4, ARRAY['maternity-leave','workplace','employment-rights','second-trimester','planning','hr'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

