('pregnancy', 8, 'Omega-3s in Pregnancy: Why DHA Matters for Baby Brain Development',
 'The essential fatty acid that supports your baby''s brain and eyes \u2014 and how to get enough',
 E'## What are omega-3 fatty acids?\n\nOmega-3 fatty acids are a family of essential fats \u2014 meaning the body cannot make them in sufficient quantities and they must come from diet. Three types matter most: ALA (found in plant foods), EPA, and DHA (both found primarily in fatty fish and algae).\n\nDHA (docosahexaenoic acid) is particularly critical during pregnancy. It is a structural component of brain cell membranes and the retina of the eye, and it accumulates rapidly in the fetal brain during the second and especially the third trimester.\n\n## Why DHA needs are higher in pregnancy\n\nYour baby''s DHA supply comes entirely through you. During the third trimester especially, the fetal brain undergoes rapid growth \u2014 a process called the brain growth spurt \u2014 and DHA demand peaks. If your own DHA levels are inadequate, your reserves will be drawn on to supply the baby.\n\n## How much do you need?\n\nMost guidelines recommend 200\u2013300mg of DHA per day during pregnancy. Some recommend up to 600mg. Many people do not meet this through diet alone.\n\n## Dietary sources\n\n**Oily fish (highest DHA concentration):** Salmon, sardines, herring, mackerel, anchovies. These are also low in mercury.\n\n**Limit:** Tuna (especially bigeye and albacore), swordfish, shark, king mackerel \u2014 high mercury content.\n\n**Algae-based DHA supplements:** An excellent option for vegetarians, vegans, and those who do not eat fish. Algae is actually the original source of DHA in fish (fish get it from eating algae or smaller fish). Algae-based DHA is safe and effective in pregnancy.\n\n**Flaxseed, chia seeds, walnuts:** Contain ALA, which the body can convert to DHA \u2014 but conversion rates are low (around 5%). These are useful additions but not sufficient as a sole source.\n\n## Should you supplement?\n\nIf you eat 1\u20132 portions of oily fish per week, you may be meeting your DHA needs through diet. If not, a pregnancy-specific omega-3 supplement (or algae-based DHA supplement) is worth discussing with your provider.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Discuss supplementation with your healthcare provider or dietitian.*',
 'nutrition', 4, ARRAY['omega-3','dha','fish','brain-development','supplements','nutrition','pregnancy'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 14, 'Calcium in Pregnancy: Dairy and Non-Dairy Sources',
 'Why calcium needs increase in pregnancy and how to meet them from any diet',
 E'## Why calcium is essential in pregnancy\n\nCalcium is the primary mineral in bone and teeth. During pregnancy, your baby''s skeleton is forming and requires a steady supply of calcium throughout, with needs increasing particularly in the third trimester when fetal bone mineralisation is most intense.\n\nIf your calcium intake is insufficient, your body will draw calcium from your own bones to supply the baby \u2014 a process that can reduce bone density and increase your own long-term osteoporosis risk.\n\n## How much calcium do you need?\n\nRecommended intake during pregnancy is 1,000mg per day for adults (1,300mg for those under 19). One cup of milk or yoghurt provides around 300mg; a serving of firm tofu made with calcium sulphate can provide 250\u2013400mg.\n\n## Dairy sources\n\n- Milk (cow, goat): approximately 300mg per 250ml cup\n- Yoghurt: approximately 300mg per 200g serving\n- Hard cheese (cheddar, parmesan): approximately 300mg per 30\u201340g serving\n- Soft cheese (cottage, ricotta): lower, approximately 80\u2013150mg per serving\n\n## Non-dairy sources\n\nFor those who do not consume dairy \u2014 whether due to lactose intolerance, allergy, veganism, or cultural preference:\n\n- **Fortified plant milks** (soy, oat, almond, rice): Most are fortified to match dairy (300mg per 250ml). Shake the carton before using, as calcium can settle.\n- **Tofu (calcium-set):** Check the label \u2014 tofu made with calcium sulphate (E516) contains 200\u2013400mg per 100g.\n- **Canned fish with bones** (sardines, salmon): approximately 300mg per serving.\n- **Leafy greens:** Bok choy, kale, broccoli, Chinese broccoli (gai lan) are good sources. Spinach and Swiss chard contain calcium but also oxalates that reduce absorption.\n- **Sesame seeds and tahini:** approximately 130mg per 2 tablespoons.\n- **Almonds:** approximately 75mg per 30g handful.\n- **Edamame and white beans:** approximately 130mg per cup.\n\n## Absorption\n\nVitamin D is essential for calcium absorption. If your vitamin D levels are low (common in many populations), calcium absorption is impaired regardless of intake. Most prenatal vitamins contain both.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider or dietitian about calcium needs in your specific context.*',
 'nutrition', 3, ARRAY['calcium','bone-health','dairy','non-dairy','vegan','nutrition','second-trimester'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 14, 'Protein Needs in Pregnancy: How Much and the Best Sources',
 'Why protein requirements increase in the second trimester \u2014 and how to meet them from any diet',
 E'## Why protein needs increase in pregnancy\n\nProtein provides the amino acid building blocks for every cell in your baby''s body. It supports fetal growth, placental development, and your own expanding blood volume and tissue. Protein needs are modest in the first trimester but increase significantly from the second trimester onward.\n\n## How much protein do you need?\n\nGeneral guidance suggests pregnant people need approximately 70\u2013100g of protein per day \u2014 compared to around 45\u201355g for non-pregnant adults. This increase is most important from around week 14, when fetal growth accelerates.\n\n## Practical protein amounts\n\n- 100g cooked chicken breast: approximately 30g protein\n- 100g salmon: approximately 25g protein\n- 2 eggs: approximately 12g protein\n- 200g Greek yoghurt: approximately 17g protein\n- 150g cooked lentils: approximately 12g protein\n- 150g cooked chickpeas: approximately 11g protein\n- 100g firm tofu: approximately 12g protein\n- 30g almonds: approximately 6g protein\n\nMost people who eat a varied diet that includes protein at each meal will meet their needs without tracking obsessively.\n\n## Plant-based protein in pregnancy\n\nVegetarian and vegan pregnancies can absolutely meet protein needs through plant sources. Key considerations:\n\n- **Completeness:** Plant proteins (except soy, quinoa, and buckwheat) are incomplete \u2014 they do not contain all essential amino acids in sufficient quantities individually. However, eating a varied diet with different protein sources throughout the day provides all essential amino acids.\n- **Soy:** One of the best plant protein sources in pregnancy \u2014 complete, high in protein, and safe. No evidence supports avoiding soy during pregnancy.\n- **Legumes and grains:** Classic combinations (rice and beans, bread and hummus) together provide complete protein.\n\n## Signs of inadequate protein intake\n\nExcessive fatigue beyond normal pregnancy tiredness, poor wound healing, and unusual swelling can sometimes indicate inadequate protein. Speak with a dietitian if you have concerns.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with a registered dietitian if you have specific dietary needs or concerns.*',
 'nutrition', 3, ARRAY['protein','nutrition','second-trimester','plant-based','diet','amino-acids'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 4, 'Hydration in Pregnancy: How Much Water and What Counts',
 'Why hydration becomes more critical in pregnancy and practical ways to stay well hydrated',
 E'## Why hydration matters more in pregnancy\n\nYour body''s fluid needs increase substantially during pregnancy. Blood volume expands by around 50%. Amniotic fluid \u2014 the protective liquid surrounding your baby \u2014 is constantly produced and replenished. Your kidneys are processing significantly more fluid. Adequate hydration supports all of this, as well as nutrient transport, temperature regulation, and digestion.\n\nDehydration in pregnancy is associated with increased risk of urinary tract infections, constipation, headaches, dizziness, and in later pregnancy, potentially triggering uterine contractions.\n\n## How much to drink\n\nMost guidelines suggest 2\u20133 litres (8\u201312 cups) of fluid per day during pregnancy, with higher needs if you are in a hot climate, physically active, or experiencing vomiting.\n\nThis can feel like a lot, especially if nausea is making fluid intake difficult. The goal is steady consumption throughout the day rather than drinking large amounts at once.\n\n## What counts toward your fluid intake\n\nAll fluids count toward hydration, not just water:\n\n- Water (still or sparkling)\n- Herbal teas (check which are safe \u2014 see below)\n- Decaffeinated tea and coffee\n- Milk and plant milks\n- Soups and broths\n- Fresh fruit juices (pasteurised, limited quantities due to sugar content)\n- Foods with high water content: cucumber, watermelon, tomatoes, oranges, lettuce\n\n## Caffeine limits\n\nCaffeinated drinks count toward fluid intake but caffeine has a mild diuretic effect and has been associated with increased miscarriage risk at higher intakes. Most guidelines recommend a maximum of 200mg of caffeine per day.\n\n## Herbal teas in pregnancy\n\nMany herbal teas are safe; some are not. Safe in moderation: ginger, peppermint, chamomile, rooibos, lemon balm. Avoid: pennyroyal, dong quai, blue cohosh, yarrow, high doses of liquorice root. When in doubt, check with your provider.\n\n## Signs of dehydration\n\nDark yellow urine, reduced urine output, headache, dizziness, dry mouth, and constipation are all signs that you need more fluid.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider if you are struggling to maintain adequate hydration, particularly if vomiting is severe.*',
 'nutrition', 3, ARRAY['hydration','water','fluids','first-trimester','herbal-tea','caffeine','dehydration'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 8, 'Vegetarian and Vegan Pregnancy Nutrition: What You Need to Know',
 'A plant-based pregnancy is entirely achievable with targeted attention to a handful of key nutrients',
 E'## Can you have a healthy vegan or vegetarian pregnancy?\n\nYes \u2014 absolutely. Plant-based diets can meet all nutritional needs during pregnancy, and many do so with thoughtful planning. The key is being intentional about a small number of nutrients that are less abundant or less bioavailable from plant sources.\n\n## Nutrients requiring special attention\n\n**Vitamin B12 (vegans especially).** B12 is found almost exclusively in animal products. Deficiency during pregnancy can cause neurological damage in both mother and baby. Vegans must supplement B12 \u2014 no plant food provides reliable amounts. Lacto-ovo vegetarians who regularly eat dairy and eggs may be adequate, but testing is advisable.\n\n**Iron.** Plant-based iron (non-haem iron) is less efficiently absorbed than animal-based haem iron. Boost absorption by pairing iron-rich foods with vitamin C, and avoid tea and coffee within an hour of iron-rich meals. Regular blood count monitoring is especially important.\n\n**Omega-3 DHA.** ALA from flaxseed, chia, and walnuts converts poorly to DHA. An algae-based DHA supplement is strongly recommended for vegetarians and vegans in pregnancy.\n\n**Calcium.** Well achievable from fortified plant milks, calcium-set tofu, leafy greens, and tahini \u2014 but requires active inclusion in the diet.\n\n**Iodine.** Found mainly in dairy and seafood. Seaweed is inconsistent and can contain excessive iodine. A supplement containing iodine (around 150\u2013200mcg) is recommended for vegans in pregnancy.\n\n**Zinc.** Present in legumes, seeds, and whole grains \u2014 but phytates in these foods reduce absorption. Soaking and sprouting legumes helps. Varied intake across the day is protective.\n\n**Vitamin D.** Deficiency is widespread across all dietary patterns. Supplementation is recommended for most people in pregnancy.\n\n## Protein\n\nEntirely achievable on a plant-based diet through legumes, tofu, tempeh, edamame, quinoa, and nuts \u2014 provided variety and adequate quantity are maintained.\n\n## Getting support\n\nA registered dietitian who is knowledgeable about plant-based diets and pregnancy is an excellent investment. Many can offer telehealth consultations.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Speak with your healthcare provider and consider working with a registered dietitian during a vegan or vegetarian pregnancy.*',
 'nutrition', 5, ARRAY['vegan','vegetarian','plant-based','b12','iron','dha','nutrition','pregnancy'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 6, 'Safe Fish in Pregnancy: Which to Eat and Which to Avoid',
 'The mercury question answered \u2014 which fish are safe and beneficial, and which to limit',
 E'## Why fish is both recommended and cautioned in pregnancy\n\nFish is one of the most nutritionally valuable foods you can eat during pregnancy \u2014 it is rich in DHA omega-3s for brain development, high-quality protein, iodine, selenium, and vitamin D. Most health authorities recommend eating fish regularly during pregnancy.\n\nThe concern is mercury. Fish accumulate mercury from their environment, and large, predatory fish at the top of the food chain have the highest concentrations. High mercury exposure during pregnancy is associated with neurological harm to the developing baby.\n\nThe solution is not to avoid fish \u2014 it is to choose the right fish.\n\n## Safe fish to eat regularly (2\u20133 portions per week)\n\nThese are low in mercury and high in nutritional value:\n\n- Salmon (wild and farmed)\n- Sardines\n- Herring\n- Mackerel (Atlantic/Pacific \u2014 NOT king mackerel)\n- Anchovies\n- Trout\n- Haddock, pollock, cod (lower DHA but safe)\n- Tilapia\n- Shrimp and prawns\n- Canned light tuna (skipjack) \u2014 up to 2\u20133 servings per week\n\n## Fish to limit\n\n- **Canned albacore (white) tuna:** Limit to 1\u20132 servings per week \u2014 higher mercury than light tuna\n- **Fresh or frozen tuna steaks:** Limit to 1 serving per week\n\n## Fish to avoid\n\nDue to high mercury levels:\n- Shark\n- Swordfish\n- King mackerel\n- Tilefish\n- Bigeye tuna (often served as sushi-grade tuna)\n- Marlin\n- Orange roughy\n\n## Raw fish (sushi)\n\nRaw fish carries a risk of parasites and bacteria. Most health guidelines advise avoiding raw fish in pregnancy, though the risk from properly handled, high-quality sushi is low. Cooked sushi and vegetable rolls are safe alternatives.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Check the guidelines from your national food safety authority for country-specific advice on fish consumption during pregnancy.*',
 'nutrition', 3, ARRAY['fish','mercury','dha','salmon','sushi','food-safety','nutrition'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 5, 'Listeria and Food Safety in Pregnancy: Foods to Avoid',
 'Why listeriosis is particularly dangerous in pregnancy and which foods pose the greatest risk',
 E'## Why Listeria is particularly dangerous in pregnancy\n\nListeria monocytogenes is a bacterium found in certain foods that can cause a serious infection called listeriosis. For most healthy adults, listeriosis causes mild flu-like symptoms. During pregnancy, it is far more serious.\n\nPregnancy suppresses certain aspects of the immune system (a necessary adaptation to prevent rejection of the fetus). This makes pregnant people around 10 times more likely to develop listeriosis than the general population. The infection can cross the placenta and cause miscarriage, stillbirth, premature labour, and serious illness in newborns.\n\nThe good news: listeriosis is rare, and the foods that carry risk are identifiable. Avoiding a specific list of foods significantly reduces risk.\n\n## High-risk foods to avoid\n\n**Soft, mould-ripened cheeses:** Brie, camembert, blue cheeses (Roquefort, stilton, gorgonzola). Listeria can survive in these even when pasteurised milk was used.\n\n**Unpasteurised (raw) dairy products:** Raw milk, raw milk cheeses.\n\n**Pate and liver spreads** (all types, including vegetable pate).\n\n**Deli meats and cold cuts** (salami, ham, prosciutto, lunch meats) unless heated until steaming.\n\n**Hot dogs and frankfurters** unless heated until steaming.\n\n**Raw sprouts** (alfalfa, bean, clover sprouts).\n\n**Pre-packaged salads and salad bars** \u2014 higher risk than freshly prepared salads.\n\n**Smoked seafood** (lox, smoked salmon, kippered fish) unless in a cooked dish.\n\n**Sushi and raw fish** (as above \u2014 bacterial and parasitic risk).\n\n## Lower risk but still worth noting\n\nPre-cut fruit left at room temperature, raw or undercooked eggs, and unpasteurised juices carry Listeria or other bacterial risks.\n\n## Hard cheeses and other safe dairy\n\nHard cheeses such as cheddar, parmesan, gruyere, and edam are safe \u2014 even if made from unpasteurised milk. Processed cheese, cream cheese, mozzarella (pasteurised), feta (pasteurised), cottage cheese, and ricotta are also safe.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Follow the food safety guidelines from your national health authority for your specific country.*',
 'safety', 4, ARRAY['listeria','food-safety','deli-meat','cheese','sushi','pregnancy','bacteria'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

