('pregnancy', 10, 'Pregnancy Anxiety: Normal Worry vs Anxiety Disorder',
 'When pregnancy worry becomes something more \u2014 and what to do about it',
 E'## Worry is normal. Anxiety disorder is different.\n\nVirtually every pregnant person worries about their pregnancy at some point. Worrying about whether the baby is healthy, whether you will be a good parent, whether the birth will be safe \u2014 these are universal and understandable concerns. They are a sign of love and investment in your pregnancy, not a sign of illness.\n\nAnxiety disorder is something different. It is characterised by worry that is excessive, persistent, difficult to control, and that significantly interferes with daily functioning or quality of life.\n\nAnxiety disorders affect around 15% of pregnant people \u2014 making them at least as common as antenatal depression, if not more so. Yet they receive far less attention.\n\n## Signs that worry may have become anxiety\n\n- You spend the majority of your waking hours worrying about your pregnancy or baby, and cannot redirect your attention even when you try\n- You seek constant reassurance (checking for heartbeats, researching symptoms obsessively) and the relief lasts only minutes before the worry returns\n- You are avoiding situations, information, or experiences because the anxiety is too overwhelming (avoiding reading anything about birth; avoiding social situations)\n- Physical symptoms: racing heart, chest tightness, shortness of breath, trembling, feeling on edge\n- Your sleep is severely disrupted by anxious thoughts\n- The anxiety is significantly affecting your relationships, work, or ability to function\n\n## Specific presentations to know\n\n**Generalised anxiety disorder (GAD):** Pervasive, uncontrollable worry across multiple domains.\n\n**Health anxiety:** Intense preoccupation with the health of the baby or your own body, driven by fear.\n\n**Tokophobia:** A specific, severe fear of childbirth that can be debilitating. More common than recognised.\n\n**OCD in pregnancy:** Intrusive thoughts about harm coming to the baby \u2014 these are ego-dystonic (the thoughts feel alien and distressing, not desired) and are a recognised form of OCD, not a sign of danger.\n\n## What helps\n\nCognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) is the most evidence-supported treatment for anxiety in pregnancy. Mindfulness-based approaches are also beneficial. Medication is an option for severe anxiety \u2014 the risk-benefit conversation is important and individual.\n\nTell your midwife, GP, or obstetrician. Raising the issue is the first step.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If you are experiencing significant anxiety in pregnancy, please speak with your healthcare provider.*',
 'mental-health', 5, ARRAY['anxiety','mental-health','pregnancy','worry','cbt','tokophobia','ocd'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 6, 'When Pregnancy Is Unplanned: Navigating Mixed Feelings',
 'Ambivalence about an unplanned pregnancy is more common than you might think \u2014 and nothing to be ashamed of',
 E'## The reality of mixed feelings\n\nThe cultural expectation is that a positive pregnancy test brings joy. But many pregnancies are unplanned or happened at a complicated time, and the feelings that accompany a positive test can be far more complex \u2014 shock, fear, grief, confusion, resentment, and yes, sometimes joy too. These feelings can coexist and they can change from hour to hour.\n\nFeeling ambivalent \u2014 even feeling that you do not want this pregnancy \u2014 does not make you a bad person. It makes you human. What matters is having space to process your feelings and access to the information and support you need to make decisions that are right for you.\n\n## You have options\n\nDepending on your location, gestational age, and circumstances, your options may include:\n\n- Continuing the pregnancy and parenting\n- Continuing the pregnancy and making an adoption plan\n- Ending the pregnancy through abortion\n\nAll three are valid choices. Access to each varies significantly by country, state, and individual circumstance. A healthcare provider, family planning clinic, or counsellor can explain what is available to you.\n\n## If you are continuing the pregnancy\n\nFeeling conflicted early on does not predict how you will feel later. Many people who felt shocked or reluctant at first go on to feel ready and connected as the pregnancy progresses. Allow yourself to move at your own pace.\n\nAt the same time, if difficult feelings persist or deepen, please reach out for support. Antenatal mental health services exist specifically to support people with complicated emotional responses to pregnancy.\n\n## Supporting yourself\n\n- Find someone you trust to talk to \u2014 a partner, friend, family member, or counsellor\n- Give yourself permission to feel whatever you feel without judgment\n- Access information from a neutral, non-judgmental source (a healthcare provider, not a search engine at 2am)\n- Know that whatever you decide, support exists\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. Please speak with a healthcare provider or counsellor if you are struggling with an unplanned pregnancy. All conversations with healthcare providers are confidential.*',
 'mental-health', 4, ARRAY['unplanned-pregnancy','ambivalence','mental-health','first-trimester','decision-making','support'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 10, 'The Partner Experience of Pregnancy: How to Support and Feel Involved',
 'Pregnancy is not a solo experience \u2014 a guide for partners who want to show up well',
 E'## The partner''s perspective is real and valid\n\nPregnancy is physically experienced by one person, but it is a profound experience for both partners. Partners often describe feeling a mix of excitement, anxiety, helplessness, and uncertainty \u2014 and sometimes feeling sidelined in appointments and conversations that centre the pregnant person.\n\nThese feelings are valid. Partners matter in this process, both for their own wellbeing and because the pregnant person''s experience is deeply shaped by the quality of their relationship support.\n\n## Practical ways to be genuinely supportive\n\n**Show up to appointments.** Being present at prenatal appointments \u2014 the booking appointment, the 12-week scan, the 20-week scan \u2014 matters. It communicates investment and keeps you informed so you are not relying on second-hand summaries.\n\n**Learn what is happening.** Understanding what is happening in the pregnancy week by week \u2014 what symptoms are normal, what tests are coming up, what milestones are approaching \u2014 helps you have informed conversations and respond with genuine empathy rather than dismissiveness.\n\n**Take on more at home.** First trimester fatigue and nausea are debilitating. Taking over cooking, cleaning, and household management without being asked is practical love.\n\n**Ask how to help \u2014 then listen.** Everyone''s needs are different. Ask what kind of support would actually help today.\n\n**Handle your own anxiety separately.** Partners carry their own pregnancy anxiety. Processing it with a friend, therapist, or peer group rather than dumping it onto the pregnant person \u2014 who is already managing their own \u2014 is important.\n\n## Bonding with the pregnancy\n\nBonding for a partner often begins later than for the pregnant person and strengthens with tangible milestones: seeing the scan, hearing the heartbeat, feeling kicks through the bump. This is normal. Active involvement \u2014 reading about development, coming to appointments, talking to the baby, preparing the nursery \u2014 supports connection.\n\n## If you are a same-sex or solo parent\n\nThe ''partner'' role in pregnancy takes many forms. Non-gestational partners in same-sex relationships, co-parents, and supportive friends and family members all benefit from the same principles: learning, showing up, and asking how to help.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If either partner is experiencing significant anxiety or other mental health difficulties during pregnancy, please seek support from a healthcare provider.*',
 'relationships', 4, ARRAY['partner','relationships','support','first-trimester','bonding','antenatal'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial'),

('pregnancy', 8, 'Pregnancy After Loss: Hypervigilance and Healing',
 'Carrying a pregnancy after miscarriage, stillbirth, or infant loss \u2014 and what to expect emotionally',
 E'## The experience of pregnancy after loss\n\nFor those who have experienced pregnancy loss \u2014 whether miscarriage, stillbirth, ectopic pregnancy, or infant death \u2014 a subsequent pregnancy is rarely the straightforward experience it might have been. The knowledge that pregnancy does not always result in a living baby changes everything.\n\nWhat many people experience is a constant state of hypervigilance: checking for symptoms, catastrophising about what their absence might mean, counting days until the next milestone, struggling to bond with the baby for fear of being hurt again.\n\nThis is not irrational. It is the entirely reasonable response of someone who has learned, in the most painful possible way, that pregnancy is uncertain.\n\n## What hypervigilance looks like\n\n- Difficulty feeling hope or joy about the pregnancy, even when things are going well\n- Counting down to milestones (the first heartbeat, the 12-week mark, the 20-week scan) without feeling lasting relief when they are reached\n- Reluctance to prepare for the baby \u2014 buying items, setting up the nursery \u2014 because it feels too risky\n- Constantly checking for symptoms or absence of symptoms\n- Dreading appointments because of what might be found\n- Difficulty connecting or talking to the baby, as a form of self-protection\n- Feeling separate from other pregnant people and from cultural narratives about pregnancy\n\n## What helps\n\n**Acknowledge that this is grief continuing, not failing.** You are navigating loss and hope simultaneously. That is genuinely hard.\n\n**Access specialist support.** Pregnancy after loss support groups (including online communities) connect you with people who understand in a way that friends and family may not. Perinatal mental health services can offer therapy specifically in this context.\n\n**Talk to your provider about additional support.** Some services offer more frequent monitoring for people with previous loss \u2014 this does not always change outcomes, but it can reduce anxiety. Ask what is available.\n\n**Set your own pace with bonding.** Protecting yourself by not fully investing emotionally is understandable. Try to find small ways to connect when you are ready, without pressure from others or yourself.\n\n**Let partners and support people in.** Loss can create emotional distance. Those who love you may not know how to help in this pregnancy \u2014 tell them.\n\n*This article is for informational purposes only. If you are struggling with your mental health during pregnancy after loss, please speak with your healthcare provider or a perinatal mental health specialist.*',
 'mental-health', 5, ARRAY['pregnancy-after-loss','miscarriage','grief','hypervigilance','mental-health','stillbirth','anxiety'], true, true, 'Lumira Editorial');
